{"title_page": "Replicas of the Statue of Liberty", "text_new": "{{original research|date=February 2016}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2011}}\nHundreds of [[replica]]s of the [[Statue of Liberty]] (''Liberty Enlightening the World'') have been created worldwide.\n\n==France==\n===Paris===\n====Mus\u00e9e d'Orsay====\n[[File:Statue de la liberte.jpg|thumb|left|The Exposition Universelle model in its previous location in the [[Jardin du Luxembourg]], Paris]]\nOn the occasion of the [[Exposition Universelle (1900)|Exposition Universelle of 1900]], sculptor [[Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Bartholdi]] crafted a smaller version of his ''Liberty Enlightening the World'', which he subsequently gave to the Mus\u00e9e du Luxembourg. In 1905, the statue was placed outside the museum in the [[Jardin du Luxembourg]], where it stood for over a century, until 2014. It currently stands within the entrance hall to the [[Mus\u00e9e d'Orsay]], and a newly constructed bronze replica stands in its place in the Jardin du Luxembourg.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.musee-orsay.fr/en/collections/overview/actualites/lady-liberty-in-orsay.html#c67912 |title=The Mus\u00e9e d'Orsay's Liberty |website=[[Mus\u00e9e d'Orsay]] |accessdate=August 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====\u00cele aux Cygnes====\n[[File:Statue of Liberty Paris 2007-05-29.jpg|thumb|Statue of Liberty on the [[\u00cele aux Cygnes]], River Seine in Paris. Given to the city in 1889, it faces southwest, downriver along the Seine.]]\nThis statue was given in 1889 to France by U.S. citizens<ref name=nytimes>{{cite news |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9D00E4DE143AEF33A25756C0A9619C94689FD7CF |title=France's Liberty Statue; A Copy of that on Bedlow's Island. Ceremonies at the Inauguration in Paris of the Replica of Bartholdi's Great Work |date=July 5, 1889 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=August 1, 2017}}</ref> living in Paris to celebrate the [[French Revolution]] three years after the main statue in New York was inaugurated. In 1937, the statue was turned from looking east to looking west straight to the direction of the New York's statue.\n\nThe statue is near the [[Pont de Grenelle|Grenelle Bridge]] on the [[\u00cele aux Cygnes]], a man-made island in the [[Seine]] ({{Coord|48|51|0|N|2|16|47|E|}}). It is {{convert|11.50|m|ftin|abbr=off}} high and weighs 14 tons.<ref name=japantimes>{{cite news |url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/1998/04/28/national/statue-illumination-kicks-off-year-of-france-event/ |title=Statue illumination kicks off \u2018Year of France\u2019 event |date=April 28, 1998 |newspaper=[[Japan Times]] |accessdate=October 4, 2015}}</ref> Inaugurated on 4 July 1889, it looks southwest, downriver along the Seine. Its tablet bears two dates: \"IV JUILLET 1776\" (4 July 1776: the [[United States Declaration of Independence]]) like the New York statue, and \"XIV JUILLET 1789\" (14 July 1789: the [[storming of the Bastille]]) associated with an equal sign. This statue is shown in the film ''[[National Treasure: Book of Secrets]]'' as a historic location.\n\n====Mus\u00e9e des Arts et M\u00e9tiers====\nThe {{convert|2.86|m|ft|adj=on}} tall original plaster [[maquette]] finished in 1878 by Auguste Bartholdi that was used to make the statue in New York is in the [[Mus\u00e9e des Arts et M\u00e9tiers]] in Paris.<ref>{{cite book |first1=Robert |last1=Belot |first2=Daniel |last2=Bermond |title=Bartholdi |location=Paris |publisher=\u00c9ditions Perrin |year=2004 |isbn=978-2-26201-991-4}}</ref><ref>E. L. Kallop, Jr., ''Images of Liberty. Models and reductions of the Statue of Liberty 1867\u20131917'', Special Centennial Exhibition 25 Janvier\u201315 F\u00e9vrier 1986</ref> This original plaster was bequeathed by the artist's widow in 1907,<ref>Legal instrument prepared by M. Demanche, notary, on 1 March 1907 (Inv13768ter in the Museum archives).</ref> together with part of the artist's estate.\n\nOn the square outside the Mus\u00e9e des Arts et M\u00e9tiers{{'}}s entrance is a bronze copy made from the plaster maquette, number 1 from an original edition of 12, made by the museum and cast by Susse Fondeur Paris.\n\n====''Flame of Liberty''====\nA life-size copy of the torch, ''[[Flame of Liberty]]'', can be seen above the entrance to the [[Pont de l'Alma]] tunnel near the [[Champs-\u00c9lys\u00e9es]] in Paris. It was given to the city as a return gift in honour of the centennial celebration of the statue's dedication. Since it is above the Pont de l'Alma car tunnel in which [[Princess Diana]] died, the torch became an unofficial memorial to the princess.<ref>{{cite magazine\n|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,624681,00.html\n|title=Paris Honors Diana with Two Memorials\n|date=August 28, 2002\n|first=Stephen M.\n|last=Silverman\n|magazine=[[People (magazine)|People]]}}</ref>\n\n===Barentin===\nThere is a replica in the northwest of France, in the small town of Barentin near [[Rouen]]. It was made for a French movie, ''Le Cerveau'' (\"The Brain\"), directed by G\u00e9rard Oury and featuring actors [[Jean-Paul Belmondo]] and [[Bourvil]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.statueofliberty.info/pages/statue/mondeba.htm |title=Les Statues dans le monde |accessdate=May 28, 2006 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060210152719/http://www.statueofliberty.info/pages/statue/mondeba.htm |archivedate=February 10, 2006 |url-status=dead |df=mdy}}: image and description of the Barentin replica from the personal website of a Statue of Liberty enthusiast.</ref>\n\n===Bordeaux===\nAnother replica is a {{convert|2.5|m|ft|abbr=on}} statue in the city of [[Bordeaux]]. The first Bordeaux statue was seized and melted down by the Nazis in World War II. The statue was replaced in 2000 and a plaque was added to commemorate the victims of the [[September 11, 2001 attacks|11 September terrorist attacks]]. On the night of 25 March 2003, unknown vandals poured red paint and gasoline on the replica and set it on fire. The vandals also cracked the pedestal of the plaque. The mayor of Bordeaux, former prime minister [[Alain Jupp\u00e9]], condemned the attack.\n\n===Colmar===\n[[File:ColmarStatueLibert\u00e9rR\u00e9plique.jpg|thumb|Replica of the Statue of Liberty in [[Colmar]]]]\nA {{convert|12|m|ftin|abbr=on}} replica of the Statue of Liberty in [[Colmar]], the city of [[Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Bartholdi|Bartholdi's]] birth, was dedicated on 4 July 2004, to commemorate the 100th anniversary of his death. It stands at the north entrance of the city.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.endex.com/gf/buildings/liberty/worldstatues/liberties/Colmar/LibertyColmar.htm |title=Statue of Freedom, Colmar, Alsace, France, Birthplace of Auguste Bartholdi |first=Gary |last=Feuerstein |website=endex.com |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100615191834/http://www.endex.com/gf/buildings/liberty/worldstatues/liberties/Colmar/LibertyColmar.htm |archivedate=June 15, 2010}}</ref> The Bartholdi Museum in Colmar contains numerous models of various sizes made by Bartholdi during the process of designing the statue.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cr.nps.gov/history/online_books/hh/11/hh11e.htm |title=Construction of the Statue |date=September 25, 2000 |website=National Park Service Historical Handbook |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604150524/http://www.cr.nps.gov/history/online_books/hh/11/hh11e.htm |archivedate=June 4, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Saint-Cyr-sur-Mer===\nFr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Bartholdi donated a copy of the Statue of Liberty to the town square of [[Saint-Cyr-sur-Mer]].\n\n===Other French cities===\nOther ''Liberty Enlightening the World'' statues are displayed in [[Poitiers]] and [[Lunel]]. The [[Mus\u00e9e des beaux-arts de Lyon]] owns a terracotta version.\n\nNear [[Chaumont, Haute Marne]], is a miniature replica in the flag plaza of the former [[Chaumont Air Base]]. This was the home of the US 48th Tactical Fighter Wing, now based at Lakenheath, England, with its own statue at the flag plaza. The 48th TFW is the only USAF wing with a name: \"The Statue of Liberty Wing\".\n\nAnother example is of a ''Liberty Enlightening the World'' replica in [[Ch\u00e2teauneuf-la-For\u00eat]], near the city of [[Limoges]] in the area of [[Haute-Vienne]], [[Limousin (region)|Limousin]]. There is another \"original\" Bartholdi replica at [[Roybon]] (near Grenoble)\n\nThere is a small replica on [[Promenade des Anglais]] in [[Nice]].\n\n==Other European countries==\n===Austria===\nIn [[Minimundus]], a [[miniature park]] located at the [[W\u00f6rthersee]] in [[Carinthia (state)|Carinthia]], Austria, is another replica of the Statue of Liberty.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.minimundus.at/img/bildarchiv/ba_10_gross.jpg |title=Minimundus replica |website=minimundus.at |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070317230345/http://www.minimundus.at/img/bildarchiv/ba_10_gross.jpg |archivedate=March 17, 2007}}</ref>\n\nIn Graz, standing between the [[Graz Opera|Opera House]] and the NextLiberty Theater, stands a steel structure built out of steel beams, that depict the original size of the statue of liberty, before the plates of the final form were being put into place. Instead of torch of flame, this depiction is holding a sword in extended left arm and a sphere in the right arm representing the world.\n\n===Denmark===\nA small replica in lego is situated in [[Legoland Billund Resort|Legoland]] in [[Billund, Denmark|Billund]].\n\n===Germany===\nA {{convert|35|m|ft|abbr=on}} copy is in the German ''[[Heide Park|Heidepark Soltau]]'' theme park, located on a lake with cruising Mississippi steamboats. It weighs 28 metric tons (31 short tons), is made of plastic foam on a steel frame with polyester cladding, and was designed by the Dutch artist Gerla Spee.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.heidepark.de/swf/assets/parkplan.jpg |title=Freizeitpark und Familienpark in Soltau |website=Heide Park Resort |accessdate=August 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Ireland===\nA green painted replica of the Statue of Liberty can be found near Mulnamina More, [[County Donegal]], Ireland.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.flickriver.com/photos/70302078@N00/3140281654 |title=Flickriver Photo |website=Flickriver.com |date=August 15, 2004 |accessdate=March 19, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Kosovo===\nA replica stands atop the Hotel Victory in [[Pristina]], Kosovo.<ref>{{cite news |last=Smith |first=Morgan |title=Investors should take a closer look at Kosovo |newspaper=[[Denver Business Journal]] |date=July 25, 2003|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/denver/stories/2003/07/28/editorial4.html |quote=It was quite a change to arrive in Pristina, where the main street is named after Bill Clinton and my hotel, the Hotel Victory, has a replica of the Statue of Liberty built on its rooftop.}}</ref>\n\n=== Netherlands ===\n[[File:Drents Vrijheidsbeeld.jpg|thumb|Replica of the Statue of Liberty in [[Assen]], the Netherlands]]\nA 33&nbsp;ft (10 m) replica has its temporary location in the Dutch city of [[Assen]]. The statue bears characteristic features that represent the culture and landscape of the region, like a can of beans instead of the original torch. The replica, by sculptor Natasja Bennink, was on display for the duration of an exhibition on American Realism in the [[Drents Museum]] until 27 May 2018.\n\n===Norway===\nA smaller replica is in the Norwegian village of [[Visnes, Rogaland|Visnes]], where the copper used in the original statue was mined.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.olavsrosa.no/en/objektinfo.aspx?id=27787 |title=Vigsnes Mining Field |website=Olavsrosa.no |date=July 28, 2007 |accessdate=March 19, 2012}}</ref> A replica is also on the facade of a pub in [[Bleik]], county of [[Nordland]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nesthus.net/index.php?p=foto&l=en&bid=Array&bi=262 |title=Nesthus |website=nesthus.net |accessdate=August 1, 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201181543/http://nesthus.net/index.php?p=foto&l=en&bid=Array&bi=262 |archivedate=February 1, 2014 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.bt.no/reise/Pa-spontanferie-mellom-himmel-og-hav-1780575.html#.UuEZm4Y1hFk |title=P\u00e5 spontanferie mellom himmel og hav |first=Christina |last=Pletten |date=July 12, 2010 |newspaper=[[Bergens Tidende]] |language=Norwegian |accessdate=August 1, 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150113130258/http://www.bt.no/reise/Pa-spontanferie-mellom-himmel-og-hav-1780575.html#.UuEZm4Y1hFk |archivedate=January 13, 2015 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Spain===\n[[File:Estatua de la libertad en Cadaqu\u00e9s - de cerca - panoramio.jpg|thumb|left|Replica of the Statue of Liberty in [[Cadaqu\u00e9s]], Spain]]\n* In 1897 a {{convert|123|cm|ftin|abbr=on}} replica in iron and bronze was erected in [[Cenicero]], Spain, to honor local fighters during the [[First Carlist War]]. In 1936 it was removed during [[Spain under Franco|the dictatorship of Francisco Franco]]. It was restored in 1976.\n* The {{ill|Rossend Ar\u00fas public library|ca|Biblioteca P\u00fablica Ar\u00fas|vertical-align=sup}} in [[Barcelona]] has in its entrance a {{convert|2|m|ftin|abbr=on}} replica from 1894. She welcomes visitors to the library, which is devoted to the [[labour movement]], [[anarchism]], and [[freemasonry]].\n* [[Cadaqu\u00e9s]], a small village that was residence of [[Salvador Dal\u00ed]], has an unusual version, with both hands up. It is on top of a small tourism information office.\n\n===Ukraine===\nThere is a unique \"sitting\" Statue of Liberty in the [[Ukraine|Ukrainian]] city of [[Lviv]]. It is a sculpture on a dome of the house (15, Freedom Avenue) built by architect Yuriy Zakharevych and decorated by sculptor [[Leandro Marconi]] in 1874\u201391.\n\n===United Kingdom===\n[[File:Statue of Liberty Leicester UK.jpg|thumb|Replica of the Statue of Liberty in [[Leicester, England]]]]\nA {{convert|17|ft|m|abbr=on}}, 9,200&nbsp;kg (9.2 tons) replica stood atop the Liberty Shoe factory in [[Leicester]], England, until 2002 when the building was demolished. The statue was put into storage while the building was replaced. The statue, which dates back to the 1920s, was initially going to be put back on the replacement building, but was too heavy, so in December 2008 following restoration, it was placed on a pedestal near Liberty Park Halls of Residence on a traffic island, \"Liberty Circus\", close to where it originally stood.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/leicestershire/7478419.stm |title=Landmark could return to skyline |date=June 27, 2008 |website=BBC News |accessdate=August 1, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.leicester.gov.uk/newssite/index01.asp?pgid=8903 |title=Work begins on replacing statue |date=November 20, 2008 |website=Leicester City Council |accessdate=August 1, 2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081227051726/http://www.leicester.gov.uk/newssite/index01.asp?pgid=8903 |archivedate=December 27, 2008}}</ref>\n\nA {{convert|10|ft|m|adj=mid|-high}} replica is in the stairwell of a bowling alley building in Warrington, England. It used to be above the entrance of a restaurant nearby.\n\nThere is also a small replica located at [[RAF Lakenheath]], England, at the base flag plaza, made from leftover copper from the original.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lakenheath.af.mil/shared/media/document/AFD-070730-006.pdf |title=Press release |page=4 |website=lakenheath.af.mil}}{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\n==North America==\n\n===Canada===\nIn [[Coquitlam]], [[British Columbia]] a small replica stands on Delestre Avenue just east of North Road.<ref>{{cite web |title=Statue of Liberty replica in Coquitlam, BC on Google Street View |url=https://www.google.ca/maps/@49.2423537,-122.8919028,3a,75y,33.39h,88.12t/data=!3m6!1e1!3m4!1sQXBS89jbWzou5rL1mmQSpw!2e0!7i13312!8i6656!6m1!1e1?hl=en |accessdate=December 20, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Steinbach, Manitoba]], There will be a construction of the replica of the Statue of Liberty in Southland Park on July 4, 2020.\n\n===Mexico===\n* In [[Campeche]], Mexico, there is a small replica in the small town of [[Palizada]].\n* In [[Durango]], Mexico, a small replica is in Parque Guadiana. This park also has other small reproductions such as the [[Eiffel Tower]] and [[Taj Mahal]].\n\n===United States===\n{{See also|Strengthen the Arm of Liberty}}\n\n* From 1902 to 2002, visitors to midtown Manhattan were occasionally disoriented by what seemed to be an impossibly nearby view of the statue. They were seeing a {{convert|30|ft|m|adj=mid|-high}} replica located at 43 West 64th Street atop the Liberty Warehouse.<ref name=\"BrooklynMuseum\">{{cite web |title=Exhibitions: Replica of the Statue of Liberty: Other Statue of Liberty Replicas |website=Brooklyn Museum |url=http://www.brooklynmuseum.org/exhibitions/statue_of_liberty/ |accessdate=February 17, 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080124100241/http://www.brooklynmuseum.org/exhibitions/statue_of_liberty/ |archivedate=January 24, 2008 |url-status=dead |df=mdy}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.forgotten-ny.com/STREET%20SCENES/STATUE/liberty.html |title=Little Liberty |website=Forgotten New York |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604220808/http://www.forgotten-ny.com/STREET%20SCENES/STATUE/liberty.html |archivedate=June 4, 2011}}</ref> In February 2002, the statue was removed by the building's owners to allow the building to be expanded.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.endex.com/gf/buildings/liberty/worldstatues/.%5Cliberties%5Csol64.htm |title=Statue of Liberty \u2014 Liberty Warehouse |first=Gary |last=Feuerstein |website=endex.com |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081015032723/http://www.endex.com/gf/buildings/liberty/worldstatues/liberties/sol64.htm |archivedate=October 15, 2008 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> It was donated to the Brooklyn Museum of Art, which installed it in its sculpture garden in October 2005 with plans to restore it on site in spring of 2006.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.brooklynmuseum.org/press/pr/2005_08_statue_of_liberty.pdf |title=Brooklyn Museum to Install Monumental Statue of Liberty Replica |website=Brooklyn Museum |date=August 2005 |accessdate=1 August 2005 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060304055325/http://www.brooklynmuseum.org/press/pr/2005_08_statue_of_liberty.pdf |archivedate=March 4, 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.brooklynmuseum.org/press/pr/2005_NovDec_Whats_Happ |title=What's Happening November\u2013December 2005 |website=Brooklyn Museum |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060218142707/http://www.brooklynmuseum.org/press/pr/2005_NovDec_Whats_Happ |archivedate=February 18, 2006}}</ref>\n* A bronze sculpture of the Statue of Liberty is on display in the Metropolitan Museum of Art in New York City.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.insecula.com/oeuvre/O0016026.html/ |title=Statue de la Libert\u00e9: El\u00e9ment 1 sur 11 |website=Insecula.com |accessdate=June 1, 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060509082947/http://www.insecula.com/oeuvre/O0016026.html |archivedate=May 9, 2006 |df=mdy}}</ref>\n* [[Duluth, Minnesota]], has a small copy on the south corner of the Duluth Entertainment Convention Center property, in the center of a clearing surrounded by pine trees where it may be passed unnoticed. It was presented to the city by some of Bartholdi's descendants residing in Duluth.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ci.duluth.mn.us/city/artscommission/otherpublicart.htm |title=Other Public Art |website=City of Duluth |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080624012727/http://www.ci.duluth.mn.us/city/artscommission/otherpublicart.htm |archivedate=June 24, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.geocaching.com/seek/log.aspx?IID=109677de-7cf1-444a-a51b-d53f970cb5d2&LID=9353315 |title=Photograph of Duluth replica |website=geocaching.com}}</ref>\n* The [[Boy Scouts of America]] celebrated their fortieth anniversary in 1950 with the theme of \"[[Strengthen the Arm of Liberty]]\".<ref>{{cite journal |title=Little Sisters of Liberty |journal=Scouting |date=October 2007 |last=Attoun |first=Marti |url=http://www.scoutingmagazine.org/issues/0710/d-wwas.html |accessdate=October 9, 2007}}</ref> Between 1949 and 1952, approximately two hundred {{convert|100|in|m|adj=on}} replicas of the statue, made of stamped copper, were purchased by Boy Scout troops and donated in 39 states in the U.S. and several of its possessions and territories. The project was the brainchild of Kansas City businessman J.P. Whitaker, who was then Scout Commissioner of the [[Kansas City Area Council]]. The copper statues were manufactured by Friedley-Voshardt Co. (Chicago, Illinois) and purchased through the Kansas City Boy Scout office by those wanting one. The statues are approximately {{convert|8+1/2|ft|m}} tall without the base, are constructed of sheet copper, weigh {{convert|290|lb|kg}}, and originally cost $350 plus freight. The mass-produced statues are not great art nor meticulously accurate (a conservator notes that \"her face isn't as mature as the real Liberty. It's rounder and more like a little girl's\"), but they are cherished, particularly since [[September 11, 2001 attacks|9/11]]. Many have been lost or destroyed, but preservationists have been able to account for about a hundred of them, and BSA Troop 101 of Cheyenne, Wyoming, has collected photographs of over 100 of them.<ref>{{cite web |last=Attoun |first=Marti |title=Restoring the Little Sisters of Lady Liberty |url=http://www.americanprofile.com/article/3455.html |website=American Profile |date=September 29, 2007 |accessdate=September 30, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080316155830/http://www.americanprofile.com/article/3455.html |archivedate=March 16, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cheyennetroop101.org/liberty/ |title=Photos and locations of more than ninety of the replicas |website=BSA Troop 101 |location=Cheyenne, Wyoming |accessdate=August 1, 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110910092649/http://www.cheyennetroop101.org/liberty/ |archivedate=September 10, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> They are commonly installed at city halls, libraries, and schools. One of these statues was sent to the Philippines. After some years at the mouth of the Pasig River, Manila, it was kept in a store room at the Scout Reservation, Makiling, Laguna, for about two decades. It is now stored at the national office of the [[Boy Scouts of the Philippines]], Manila.\n*A nine-foot-tall replica of the Statue, built in 1950, stands in [[Warner Park]] in [[Madison, Wisconsin]].<ref name=\"StatueSOS\">{{cite web | author= | year=1993 | title=Statue of Liberty Replica, (sculpture). | work=Save Outdoor Sculpture! | publisher=Inventories of American Painting and Sculpture | url=http://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?&profile=all&source=~!siartinventories&uri=full=3100001~!328309~!0#focus | accessdate= 19 May 2011 }}</ref>\n* A replica of the original statue was unveiled on 12 October 2011, at 667 Madison Avenue in [[Manhattan]]. Its owner, billionaire [[Leonard N. Stern]], purchased it after reading about it in the local news. The replica is one of only 12 cast from the original mold created by [[Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Auguste Bartholdi]] using digital surface scanning and [[lost-wax casting]] methods, and is the only one currently on public display. The statue itself is 9 feet tall and 15 feet including the pedestal on which it stands.<ref>{{cite news |last=Kusisto |first=Laura |title=A New Lady Liberty Lands |newspaper=[[Wall Street Journal]] |date=October 12, 2011 |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052970203633104576625443852552376}}</ref>\n[[File:NYNY2010.JPG|right|thumb|[[New York-New York Hotel & Casino]] in Las Vegas, complete with Statue of Liberty in the foreground.]]\n* There is a half-size replica at the [[New York-New York Hotel & Casino]] in [[Las Vegas, Nevada]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nynyhotelcasino.com/pages/hotel.asp |title=New York, New York Hotel and Casino, Las Vegas |website=nynyhotelcasino.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060613171612/http://www.nynyhotelcasino.com/pages/hotel.asp |archivedate=June 13, 2006 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Levine |first=Arthur |title=Don't Make Mine Manhattan: The Big Apple Roller Coaster at New York New York Casino Hotel |date=February 24, 2016 |url=http://themeparks.about.com/cs/lasvegas/fr/manhattanexpres.htm |work=themeparks.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.virtualtourist.com/travel/North_America/United_States_of_America/Nevada/Las_Vegas-836630/Things_To_Do-Las_Vegas-New_York_New_York-BR-1.html |title=New York, Las Vegas \u2013 Things to Do |website=VirtualTourist |accessdate=July 31, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111123045050/http://www.virtualtourist.com/travel/North_America/United_States_of_America/Nevada/Las_Vegas-836630/Things_To_Do-Las_Vegas-New_York_New_York-BR-1.html |archivedate=November 23, 2011 |df=mdy}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://users.tinyworld.co.uk/mrt/html/ht_nyny.htm |title=New York New York |website=Vegas Views |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060206082524/http://users.tinyworld.co.uk/mrt/html/ht_nyny.htm |archivedate=February 6, 2006}}</ref> In April 2011, the U.S. Postal Service announced that three billion postage stamps mistakenly based on a photograph of this replica were produced and would be sold to the public.<ref name=\"stamperror-reuters\">{{cite news |last=Allen |first=Jonathan |agency=Reuters |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/04/18/uk-usa-stamp-liberty-idUSLNE73H01S20110418 |title=Statue of Liberty postage stamp shows Las Vegas |date=April 11, 2011 |accessdate =April 11, 2011}}</ref> In November 2013, the statue's sculptor, Robert Davidson, filed a copyright infringement suit against the U.S. government.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://nypost.com/2013/12/03/sculptor-sues-postal-service-over-fake-liberty-stamp/ |title=Sculptor sues Postal Service over \"fake Liberty\" stamp |newspaper=[[The New York Post]] |date=December 3, 2013 |accessdate=December 3, 2013}}</ref>\n* Another small replica exists in Las Vegas on Route 589 near Arville St in a plaza parking lot. \n* The city of [[Sioux Falls, South Dakota|Sioux Falls]], South Dakota, erected a replacement bronze reproduction standing {{convert|9|ft|m|abbr=on}} tall in McKennan Park atop the original pedestal of a long-vanished wooden replica.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.siouxfalls.org/Parks/News/2002/July/StatueofLibertyUnveiling.aspx |title=Statue of Liberty unveiling |website=Sioux Falls Parks and Recreation |date=July 2002 }}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n[[File:Liberty Enlightening the Parkway.jpg|thumb|200px|''Liberty Enlightening the World'' replica in [[Birmingham, Alabama|Birmingham]], Alabama]]\n* A {{convert|36|ft|m|adj=mid|-tall}} bronze replica, accurately based on [[Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Bartholdi|Bartholdi's]] ''Liberty Enlightening the World'', stands in [[Vestavia Hills, Alabama|Vestavia Hills]], a suburb of [[Birmingham, Alabama]]. It was cast in 1956 at the ''Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 Antoine Durenne'' foundry in Somerville, Haut Marne, France, for placement in 1958 atop the [[Liberty National Life Insurance Company]] building in downtown Birmingham.<ref name=\"BrooklynMuseum\"/> It was relocated and placed on a {{convert|60|ft|m|adj=mid|-tall}} granite pedestal adjacent to [[Interstate 459]] in 1989.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bhamonline.com/liberty/ |title=Birmingham's Statue of Liberty |website=Birmingham Online.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060829081729/http://www.bhamonline.com/liberty/ |archivedate=August 29, 2006 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"GAStudio\">{{cite web |title=Liberty Statue |website=GA Architecture Studio |url=http://www.gastudio.com/oddlots/10_missliberty/index.html |accessdate=February 17, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090106191555/http://www.gastudio.com/oddlots/10_missliberty/index.html |archivedate=January 6, 2009 |df=mdy}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |website=Roadside America |url=http://www.roadsideamerica.com/tips/getAttraction.php3?tip_AttractionNo==13 |title=Birmingham, Alabama \u2013 Statue of Liberty Replica}}</ref>\n* Two {{convert|30|ft|m|adj=on}} copper replicas by sculptor [[Leo Lentelli]] stand atop the Liberty National Bank Building<ref name=\"BrooklynMuseum\"/> in [[Buffalo, New York]], nearly {{convert|108|m|ft|abbr=on}} above street level.<ref>{{cite web |title=Liberty Building |url=http://www.emporis.com/en/wm/bu/?id=126216 |website=Emporis}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Buffalo \u2013 Liberty Building |url=http://www.planetware.com/buffalo/liberty-building-us-ny-lib.htm |website=PlanetWare}}</ref>\n* A {{convert|25|ft|m|adj=mid|-tall}} replica sits on the ruins of the late [[Marysville Bridge]] (erected on a platform (pier)) in the Dauphin Narrows of [[Susquehanna River]] north of [[Harrisburg]]. The replica was built by a local activist [[Gene Stilp]] on July 2, 1986; it was made of Venetian blinds and stood {{convert|18|ft|m}} tall. Six years later, after it was destroyed in a windstorm, it was rebuilt by Stilp and other local citizens, of wood, metal, glass and fiberglass, to a height of {{convert|25|ft|m}}.<ref>{{cite news |last=Scolforo |first=Mark |year=2004 |url=http://www.phillyburbs.com/pb-dyn/news/103-02142004-246490.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20080108084232/http://www.phillyburbs.com/pb-dyn/news/103-02142004-246490.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=2008-01-08 |title=Master of props lends visual effects to memorable publicity campaigns |agency=Associated Press }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |website=U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service |url=http://www.fish.state.pa.us/watertrails/susqmid/trailguide.htm |title=Susquehanna River Trail: Dauphin Narrows/Statue of Liberty}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.facstaff.bucknell.edu/kochel/classes/susqriver/august31.htm |first=R. Craig |last=Kochel |title=Photograph of the Stilp statue |website=Facstaff.bucknell.edu |date= |accessdate=March 19, 2012}}</ref>\n* A [[Lego]] replica of the Statue of Liberty consisting of 2882 bricks and standing {{convert|0.9|m|ft|abbr=on}} is a popular sculpture among Lego enthusiasts. The statue went out of production, but due to popular demand was returned to sale.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.roadsideamerica.com/story/10907 |title=Statue of Liberty Sculpture (#3450-1) |website=RoadSide America |date= |accessdate=July 31, 2012}}</ref>\n* A 1/12 replica of the Statue of Liberty made essentially out of junk stands at the intersection of [[US 280]] and [[US 341]] in [[McRae, Georgia]]. The head is made out of a stump from a nearby swamp, the arm holding the torch is made from [[styrofoam]] and the hand holding the book is actually an electric lineman's glove. The town's [[Lion's Club]] erected the replica in 1986 during the statue's centennial.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.roadsideamerica.com/story/10907 |title=Home-Built Statue of Liberty Replica |website=RoadSide America |date= |accessdate=May 31, 2017}}</ref>\n* An {{convert|11|ft|m|adj=on}} miniature Statue of Liberty (holding a Bible instead of a tablet) currently stands atop a {{convert|15|ft|m|adj=on}} pedestal outside the Liberty Recycling plant in [[San Marcos, California]]. The company was named after the statue, which has been moved throughout [[San Diego North County|northern San Diego County]] for over 80 years, originating at the Liberty Hotel in [[Encinitas, California|Leucadia]], in the 1920s.<ref>{{cite news |newspaper=[[North County Times]] |url=http://www.nctimes.com/news/local/article_4dd6b10d-d720-546e-85f9-69ac5553c1b0.html |title=Lady Liberty lowered in San Marcos |access-date=October 17, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100523160736/http://www.nctimes.com/news/local/article_4dd6b10d-d720-546e-85f9-69ac5553c1b0.html |archive-date=May 23, 2010 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n* A {{convert|25|ft|m|adj=on}} replica of the statue, lofting a Christian cross, holding the Ten Commandments, and named the ''Statue of Liberation through Christ'', was erected by a predominantly African American church in [[Memphis, Tennessee]], on 4 July 2006.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thestatueofliberationthroughchrist.org/ |title=Home |website=thestatueofliberationthroughchrist.org}}</ref>\n* A small replica stands on the grounds of the [[Cherokee]] Capitol Building in [[Tahlequah, Oklahoma]], a gift from the local [[Scouting in Oklahoma|Boy Scouts]] in 1950 (presumably as part of the above-mentioned national Boy Scout celebration).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lasr.net/leisure/oklahoma/cherokee/tahlequah/att3f.html |title=Statue of Liberty Replica |website=Leisure and Sport Review |year=2006 |accessdate=October 7, 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060904193624/http://www.lasr.net/leisure/oklahoma/cherokee/tahlequah/att3f.html |archive-date=September 4, 2006 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n* [[Fargo, North Dakota]], also had a replica of the Statue of Liberty on the corner of Main Avenue and 2nd Street at the entrance of the Main Avenue bridge, which was reported stolen on July 26th, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kfgo.com/news/articles/2019/jul/27/fargos-statue-of-liberty-stolen-no-questions-no-charges-if-its-returned/922028/|title=Fargo's Statue of Liberty stolen - no questions, no charges if it's returned|last=Inc|first=Midwest Communications|website=The Mighty 790 KFGO|access-date=2019-08-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |website=Digital Horizons |title=Statue of Liberty replica, Fargo, N.D. |url=http://digitalhorizonsonline.org/cdm/ref/collection/uw/id/5888 |accessdate=14 December 2014}}</ref>\n* There is a replica on the shoreline of [[Lake Chaubunagungamaug]] in [[Webster, Massachusetts]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Belluck |first=Pam |title=What's the Name of That Lake? It's Hard to Say |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=November 20, 2004 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/11/20/national/20lake.html}}</ref>\n* A 1/6-scale replica (\u224850 feet including pedestal) stands in a parking lot of a strip mall in [[Milwaukie, Oregon]], off McLoughlin Blvd at 4255 SE Roethe Rd.<ref>{{cite web |website=Roadside America |url=http://www.roadsideamerica.com/tip/15118 |title=Milwaukee, OR Statue of Liberty Replica}}</ref>\n* A {{convert|6|ft|adj=on}} replica stands at [[Statue of Liberty (Seattle)|Statue of Liberty Plaza]] in [[West Seattle]], Washington, at [[Alki Beach Park]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kuow.org/post/seattles-tiny-statue-liberty-0 |title=Seattle's Tiny Statue of Liberty |first=Joshua |last=McNichols |website=kuow.org |accessdate=August 1, 2017}}</ref>\n* A replica of the Statue of Liberty stands on [[Mackinac Island]], [[Michigan]].<ref>https://bree1972.wordpress.com/2013/09/12/lady-liberty-returns-to-mackinac-island/</ref>\n* A replica of the Statue of Liberty is located in the downtown area of New Castle, Pennsylvania.<ref name=\"visitlawrencecounty.com\">https://www.visitlawrencecounty.com/local-attractions/featured-attractions/statues-of-liberty/</ref>\n* A replica of the Statue of Liberty is located near the Lincoln High School in Ellwood City, Pennsylvania.<ref name=\"visitlawrencecounty.com\"/>\n* A bronze replica of the Statue of Liberty resides in Neenah, WI. It was cast in California by the Great American Bronze Works. This version of the Statue of Liberty is 14 feet, 6 inches tall. It is 10 percent the size of the original.<ref>http://www.waymarking.com/waymarks/WMCYYB_Statue_of_Liberty_Neenah_WI</ref><ref>http://www.bronzeking.com/Gallery/Sculptures/Monumentals/StatueOfLiberty.html</ref>\n* A replica approximately the same size as an adult person is located alongside Highway 80 at the west end of [[Forney, Texas]].  An earlier installation stood from 1986 until May 2016, when it was removed to make way for highway construction.  As of November, 2019, it has been replaced in nearly the same spot, this time painted a darker green and with a illuminated torch.<ref>https://www.inforney.com/local-news/construction-underway-to-replace-forney-s-replica-statue-of-liberty/article_bd8c9840-d044-11e9-96c8-eb05b4cfbc74.html</ref>\n\nIn Lake Michigan campground in [[Wisconsin]], There will be a new sculpture park, The first artifact will be the Statue of Liberty, It will be designed by many architects from [[New York (state)|New York]], [[Pennsylvania]], [[Florida]], [[France]], [[Minnesota]], and of course, Wisconsin, It will be under construction on June 5, 2020.\n\n==South America==\n===Argentina===\nIn [[Buenos Aires]] there is a small iron replica in Barrancas de Belgrano Square, cast by Bartholdi from the same mould as those cast in Paris; although it is much smaller. It was inaugurated on 3 October 1886, 25 days before the one in New York. Another replica was bought by the government and placed in a school, Colegio Nacional Sarmiento, about the same date.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://turismo.perfil.com/18897-un-paseo-por-la-estatua-de-la-libertad-y-sus-hermanas-gemelas/ |title=Un paseo por la Estatua de la Libertad (y sus hermanas gemelas) |date=May 31, 2013 |newspaper=[[Perfil]] |accessdate=August 1, 2017}}</ref> There is another replica in Plaza Libertad (Liberty Square) in the city of [[Villa Aberastain]], [[San Juan Province, Argentina|San Juan]]. This one arrived at the city in 1909 due to a confusion since it had to be shipped to San Juan, Puerto Rico instead. There are also two cheaper non-metallic replicas; one is 6 m tall, located in the \"New York\" Casino in [[San Luis, Argentina|San Luis]] and the other crowns a commercial gallery, \"Galer\u00eda de Fabricantes\", in [[Munro]], a city in the northeast suburbs of Buenos Aires.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.taringa.net/posts/info/17176133/La-estatua-de-la-libertad-argentina.html |title=La Estatua de la Libertad, Argentina |website=taringa.net |accessdate=August 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Brazil===\n[[File:2010-10-30 replica Statue of Liberty Maceio Alagoas Brazil.JPG|thumb|A replica of the [[Statue of Liberty]] in [[Macei\u00f3]], Alagoas, Brazil]]\n[[File:Barra.100.jpg|thumb|New York City Center in [[Rio de Janeiro]], Brazil]]\nIn [[Bangu, Rio de Janeiro]] exists a [[nickel]] replica made by [[Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Auguste Bartholdi|Bartholdi]] in 1899. Bartholdi was commissioned by [[Jos\u00e9 Paranhos, Baron of Rio Branco]] to make a replica in order to celebrate the 10th anniversary of the [[Brazil|Republic of Brazil]]. Until 1940, the statue was Paranhos family property. In 1940 the statue was passed to [[Guanabara State]]. In 20 January 1964 [[Carlos Lacerda]], governor of [[Guanabara State]], placed the statue in Miami Square, [[Bangu, Rio de Janeiro|Bangu]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blogdaalessandravieira.blogspot.com/2011/11/historia-de-que-estatua-da-liberdade.html |first=Alessandra |last=Vieira |title=Historia de que estatua da liberdade |date=November 2011 |website=Blogspot.com |accessdate=August 1, 2017}}</ref>\n{{Coord|-22.856681 |-43.492577}}\n\nA small-scale cast metal replica can be found in [[Macei\u00f3]], the capital of [[Alagoas]] State, in northeast Brazil. The replica is in front of a building constructed in 1869 as the seat of the ''Conselho Provincial'' (Provincial Council), and which today is the Museu da Imagem e do Som de Alagoas (Museum of Image and Sound of Alagoas). This replica is possibly a casting produced by the {{ill|Fundi\u00e7\u00e3o Val d'Osne|pt|Fundi\u00e7\u00e3o Val d'Osne|vertical-align=sup}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.revistadehistoria.com.br/v2/home/?go=detalhe&id=2341 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120914094154/http://www.revistadehistoria.com.br/v2/home/?go=detalhe&id=2341 |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 14, 2012 |title=Quando o ferro virou arte |website=Revista de Hist\u00f3ria |date=December 4, 2009 |accessdate=July 31, 2012}}</ref> in France, as in the Pra\u00e7a Lavenere Machado (formerly Pra\u00e7a Dois Le\u00f5es) on the opposite side of the museum, there are four somewhat larger-than-life size cast metal statues of wild animals, at least one of which is embossed with the name of the foundry. These castings and the replica all appear to be made of similar material and to be of similar age. It is also probable that they are near contemporaries of the actual Statue of Liberty.\n{{Coord|-9.6728563|-35.7223114}}\n\nA large modern replica stands in front of the New York City Center, a shopping center constructed in 1999 in [[Barra da Tijuca]] in the [[Rio de Janeiro (state)|State of Rio de Janeiro]].\n{{Coord|-22.9992837|-43.360481}}\n\nThe Havan department store chain has replicas in many of their stores. The largest one of these, 57 meters tall,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://folha1.blogspot.com.br/2012/10/conheca-as-5-maiores-estatuas-do-brasil.html |title=Conhe\u00e7a as 5 Maiores Est\u00e1tuas do Brasil |author=Guilherme |date=October 2012 |website=blogspot.com.br |accessdate=August 1, 2017}}</ref> is allegedly in the [[Barra Velha]] branc, in the state of [[Santa Catarina (state)|Santa Catarina]].{{Coord|-26.635870|-48.698708}} There is another large replica the parking area of a Havan Department Store on the outskirts of [[Curitiba]], in the [[Paran\u00e1 (state)|State of Paran\u00e1]], opened in 2000.\n{{Coord|-25.4639912|-49.2521676}}\n\nAlso, there is a small replica of the statue in [[Bel\u00e9m]], in front of a Bel\u00e9m Importados store, near the city's port.\n\n===Ecuador===\nIn [[Guayaquil]], a little replica gives the name of \"New York\" to a neighborhood in the Valle Alto area.\n\n===Peru===\nIn [[Lima]] the New York Casino in the [[Jes\u00fas Mar\u00eda District, Lima|Jes\u00fas Mar\u00eda District]] has a small replica in the main entrance. The casino is a tribute to the state of New York and the USA.\n\n==Asia==\n===[[India]]===\nA small replica can be found in [[Vardhaman Fantasy]], an amusement park in Mira Road, [[Mumbai]] along with other six [[wonders of the world]].\n\nThe 7 wonders of the world are made in Eco Park, Kolkata, West Bengal\n\nAnother small replica can be found in [[Seven Wonders Park]], a park in Kotri, [[Kota, Rajasthan|Kota]], [[Rajasthan]] along with other six [[wonders of the world]].\n\n===Malaysia===\nA large replica can be found in [[Genting Highlands]] in the state of [[Pahang]].\n\n===Singapore===\nA small replica can be found in [[Haw Par Villa]], a theme park.\n\n===China===\n====Guangzhou====\nSet on top of the memorial tomb of \"72 Martyrs of Huanghuagang\" (see [[Huanghuagang Uprising]]). The current one was re-built in 1981.\n\n====Beijing====\nDuring the [[Tiananmen Square protests of 1989|Tiananmen Square protest of 1989]], Chinese student demonstrators in Beijing built a 10&nbsp;m (33&nbsp;ft) image called the ''[[Goddess of Democracy]]'', which sculptor Tsao Tsing-yuan said was intentionally \"dissimilar\" to the Statue of Liberty to avoid being \"too openly pro-American.\" (See article for a list of replicas of that statue.)\n\n====Shenzhen====\nA replica can be found in [[Window of the World]] Park.\n\n===Israel===\n\nA 15 foot high replica of the Statue of Liberty is at the western entrance of the village of [[Arraba, Galilee|Arraba]] in Israel, near a local restaurant.\n\nAt a highway intersection in [[Jerusalem]] called \"New York Square,\" there is an abstract skeletal replica of the statue.\n\n===Japan===\n\nThe French Statue of Liberty from the [[\u00cele aux Cygnes]] came to [[Odaiba]], [[Tokyo]], from April 1998 to May 1999 in commemoration of \"The French year in Japan\".<ref name=japantimes /> Because of its popularity, in 2000 a replica of the French Statue of Liberty was erected at the same place. Also in Japan, a small Statue of Liberty is in the [[Amerikamura|Amerika-mura]] (''American Village'') shopping district in [[Osaka]], Japan. Another replica is in [[Oirase, Aomori|Oirase]]<ref>{{cite news |last=Osumi |first=Magdalena |url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/culture/2013/09/26/events/events-outside-tokyo/floats-make-oirase-fest-a-treat/ |title=Floats make Oirase fest a treat |date=September 26, 2013 |newspaper=[[Japan Times]] |accessdate=October 4, 2015}}</ref> near the town of [[Shimoda, Aomori|Shimoda]] south of [[Misawa, Aomori|Misawa]] in [[Aomori Prefecture]], where the United States has an 8,000-person [[U.S. Air Force]] base. A replica of the Statue of Liberty in [[Ishinomaki, Miyagi|Ishinomaki, Miyagi Prefecture]], was damaged by the [[2011 T\u014dhoku earthquake and tsunami]].<ref>{{cite news |last=MacLeod |first=Calum |url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/news/world/2011-03-16-japanstruggle16_ST_N.htm |title=Public order still rules amid devastation in Japan |date=March 16, 2011 |newspaper=[[USA Today]] |accessdate=October 4, 2015}}</ref> There is also a replica in [[Oyabe, Toyama|Oyabe]], [[Toyama Prefecture|Toyama]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/%E3%80%92932-0134+Toyama-ken,+Oyabe-shi,+Hirazakura,+%E8%87%AA%E7%94%B1%E3%81%AE%E5%83%8F/@36.8045769,133.3038557,6.8z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x5ff82beb66df6583:0xea33d5b10148d1c6!8m2!3d36.6290409!4d136.8444317|title=Google Maps, \u81ea\u7531\u306e\u50cf, Oyabe Toyama|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n===Pakistan===\nThere are replicas of the Statue of Liberty in [[Bahria Town]], [[Lahore]], and also in [[Bahria Town Phase 8]], [[Islamabad]].\n\n===Philippines===\nAs early as January 1945, there were already news of a campaign that would help erect a Statue of Liberty replica in the [[Philippines]]. The said monument was supposed to be sponsored by The Chicago Daily Times whose goal was \u201cto commemorate one of the great epics in the struggle for human freedom\u2013the liberation of the Philippines.\u201d\n\nFast forward to 1950, the Boy Scouts of America was celebrating its 40th anniversary. Jack P. Whitaker, then Scout Commissioner of the Kansas City Area Council, had earlier suggested the creation and distribution of several Statue of Liberty replicas to all American states and territories, including the Philippines.\n\n[[File:Carlos P. Romulo (on the left) and Arthur A. Shuck.jpg|thumb|Chief Scout Executive Arthur A. Shuck presenting to [[Carlos P. Romulo]] a miniature of the Statue of Liberty in April 1950.]]\n\nThe eight-foot statues, which were cast in bronze, were distributed all over the U.S. and the world from 1949 to 1951. Almost 200 replicas were delivered to the 39 states of the U.S. and countries such as Panama and Puerto Rico. The [[Boy Scouts of the Philippines]], on the other hand, received its own replica in the early part of 1950.\n\nThe statues were donated by the Boy Scouts of America as \u201can expression of scout brotherhood and goodwill.\u201d Not surprisingly, their 40th anniversary theme was \u201cStrengthen the Arm of Liberty.\u201d\n\nMiniature versions of the statue were also given as gifts. In fact, the Philippines became the first independent nation to receive one of the 4,000 eight-inch statues from the Boy Scouts of America. In April 1950, the said statue was officially given by Chief Scout Executive Arthur A. Shuck to [[Carlos P. Romulo]], then chief of the Philippine Mission to the United Nations.\n\nIn the Philippines, several places were suggested as the site where the eight-foot bronze replica would be erected. The task of choosing the perfect site was delegated to the National Urban Planning Commission, and among those it considered were \u201cEngineer Island, atop the proposed reviewing stand on the [[Rizal Park]], and on the center island rotunda between the [[Old Legislative building]] and [[Manila City Hall]].\u201d\n\nIn the end, the [[Boy Scouts of the Philippines]] (BSP) erected the statue just outside [[Intramuros]]. As the icon of the United States, the replica of Lady Liberty would survive several attacks by student protesters in the 1960s. It remained standing until the early 1970s, when the BSP decided to transfer it to the Scout Reservation in [[Mt. Makiling]] which would serve as the statue's home for two decades or so.\n\nIn a 2002 article published by the Philippine Star, then BSP PR head Nixon Canlapan revealed that the Statue of Liberty was eventually moved and stored at the BSP headquarters on Concepcion Street (now Natividad Almeda-Lopez) in Ermita, Manila.\n\nTurns out, the American-sponsored replica was not the first Lady Liberty in [[Manila]]. In the 1930s, one of Manila's biggest shopping stores at that time became the talk of the town not just for its products but also for its unique multi-story building. Located in Juan Luna Street, the L.R. Aguinaldo's Emporium had an Art Deco facade featuring two contrasting statues: [[Andres Bonifacio]] on the right and the Statue of Liberty on the left.\n\n[[File:Souvenir postcard featuring the L.R. Aguinaldo Building in Juan Luna St., Manila.jpg|thumb|Established by the Philippine retailing pioneer Leopoldo R. Aguinaldo, the L.R. Aguinaldo's Emporium was once one of the biggest shopping stores in pre-war Manila, located in Juan Luna Street, Manila. The multi-story building's facade featured a statue of Andres Bonifacio on the right and a replica of the statue of Liberty on the left.]]\n\nEstablished by Philippine retailing pioneer Leopoldo R. Aguinaldo, the store would later become known as the Aguinaldo's Department Store. After the war, Leopoldo's son Francisco took over the business and the store was moved to Echague.\n\nThe Echague branch in the 1950s was known for introducing its customers to quality products both from the Philippines and abroad. It also commissioned young interior designers to update the store's furniture section. Thus, the store catapulted the careers of famous designers like Myra Cruz, Edgar Ramirez, and Bonnie Ramos, among others. Aguinaldo's succumbed to the competition and closed in the 1960s. The original building in Juan Luna Street still stands, along with both the Bonifacio and the Liberty statues.\n\nSince the creation of the Liberty statues in Intramuros and Juan Luna Street, other Philippine provinces soon followed suit. Statue of Liberty replicas in can be found in [[Pangasinan]] and as far as [[Camp John Hay]] amphitheater in [[Baguio City]].\n\n===Thailand===\n\nThe Mini Siam and Mini Europe [[Miniature park|model village]], in [[Pattaya]], has a miniature Statue of Liberty amongst others.\n\n===Taiwan===\nThere are at least two Statue of Liberty replicas (greater than 30 feet in height) in [[Taiwan]]. These two statues are in the cities of [[Keelung]] and [[Taipei]].<ref>{{cite web |author=Sandy H. \u4f55\u8056\u6b23 |url=http://sandyintaiwan.blogspot.com/2007/08/statues-of-liberty.html#links |title=Sandy's Neipu Notebook: Statues of Liberty |website=Blogspot.com |date=August 30, 2007 |accessdate=July 31, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Vietnam===\nFrom 1887 to 1945, [[Hanoi]] was home to another copy of the statue. Measuring {{convert|2.85|m|ftin|abbr=on}} tall, it was erected by the French colonial government after being sent from France for an exhibition. It was known to locals unaware of its history as ''{{ill|T\u01b0\u1ee3ng B\u00e0 \u0111\u1ea7m x\u00f2e|vi|T\u01b0\u1ee3ng b\u00e0 \u0111\u1ea7m x\u00f2e|vertical-align=sup}}'' (''Statue of the madame saux''). When the French lost control of [[French Indochina]] during World War II, the statue was toppled on 1 August 1945, after being deemed a vestige of the colonial government along with other statues erected by the French.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://vietnamnet.vn/thuhanoi/2005/08/474419/ |title=H\u00e0 N\u1ed9i t\u1eebng c\u00f3 t\u01b0\u1ee3ng Th\u1ea7n T\u1ef1 Do tr\u00ean n\u00f3c Th\u00e1p R\u00f9a? |trans-title=Has Hanoi ever had the Statue of Liberty on the roof of the Turtle Tower? |website=Vietnam Net |language=Vietnamese |date=1 August 2005 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060708104847/http://www.vietnamnet.vn/thuhanoi/2005/08/474419/ |archivedate=July 8, 2006 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Australia==\nA 30-foot replica can also be seen at the [[Westfield Marion]] shopping complex in [[Adelaide]], South Australia.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Replicas of the Statue of Liberty}}\n* [http://www.statue-de-la-liberte.com/en/Copies-of-the-statue-of-Liberty.php Statues of Liberty in the world]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110910092649/http://www.cheyennetroop101.org/liberty/ Replica Statue of Liberty Search]\n* [http://architecturalwonder.blogspot.com/2010/07/statue-of-liberty.html Quick view of Statue of Liberty]\n\n{{Statue of Liberty|state=expanded}}\n{{Appropriation in the arts}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Replicas Of The Statue Of Liberty}}\n[[Category:Liberty symbols]]\n[[Category:Lists of replicas]]\n[[Category:Outdoor sculptures]]\n[[Category:Replicas of the Statue of Liberty| ]]\n[[Category:Scale modeling]]\n", "text_old": "{{original research|date=February 2016}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2011}}\nHundreds of [[replica]]s of the [[Statue of Liberty]] (''Liberty Enlightening the World'') have been created worldwide.\n\n==France==\n===Paris===\n====Mus\u00e9e d'Orsay====\n[[File:Statue de la liberte.jpg|thumb|left|The Exposition Universelle model in its previous location in the [[Jardin du Luxembourg]], Paris]]\nOn the occasion of the [[Exposition Universelle (1900)|Exposition Universelle of 1900]], sculptor [[Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Bartholdi]] crafted a smaller version of his ''Liberty Enlightening the World'', which he subsequently gave to the Mus\u00e9e du Luxembourg. In 1905, the statue was placed outside the museum in the [[Jardin du Luxembourg]], where it stood for over a century, until 2014. It currently stands within the entrance hall to the [[Mus\u00e9e d'Orsay]], and a newly constructed bronze replica stands in its place in the Jardin du Luxembourg.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.musee-orsay.fr/en/collections/overview/actualites/lady-liberty-in-orsay.html#c67912 |title=The Mus\u00e9e d'Orsay's Liberty |website=[[Mus\u00e9e d'Orsay]] |accessdate=August 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====\u00cele aux Cygnes====\n[[File:Statue of Liberty Paris 2007-05-29.jpg|thumb|Statue of Liberty on the [[\u00cele aux Cygnes]], River Seine in Paris. Given to the city in 1889, it faces southwest, downriver along the Seine.]]\nThis statue was given in 1889 to France by U.S. citizens<ref name=nytimes>{{cite news |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9D00E4DE143AEF33A25756C0A9619C94689FD7CF |title=France's Liberty Statue; A Copy of that on Bedlow's Island. Ceremonies at the Inauguration in Paris of the Replica of Bartholdi's Great Work |date=July 5, 1889 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=August 1, 2017}}</ref> living in Paris to celebrate the [[French Revolution]] three years after the main statue in New York was inaugurated. In 1937, the statue was turned from looking east to looking west straight to the direction of the New York's statue.\n\nThe statue is near the [[Pont de Grenelle|Grenelle Bridge]] on the [[\u00cele aux Cygnes]], a man-made island in the [[Seine]] ({{Coord|48|51|0|N|2|16|47|E|}}). It is {{convert|11.50|m|ftin|abbr=off}} high and weighs 14 tons.<ref name=japantimes>{{cite news |url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/1998/04/28/national/statue-illumination-kicks-off-year-of-france-event/ |title=Statue illumination kicks off \u2018Year of France\u2019 event |date=April 28, 1998 |newspaper=[[Japan Times]] |accessdate=October 4, 2015}}</ref> Inaugurated on 4 July 1889, it looks southwest, downriver along the Seine. Its tablet bears two dates: \"IV JUILLET 1776\" (4 July 1776: the [[United States Declaration of Independence]]) like the New York statue, and \"XIV JUILLET 1789\" (14 July 1789: the [[storming of the Bastille]]) associated with an equal sign. This statue is shown in the film ''[[National Treasure: Book of Secrets]]'' as a historic location.\n\n====Mus\u00e9e des Arts et M\u00e9tiers====\nThe {{convert|2.86|m|ft|adj=on}} tall original plaster [[maquette]] finished in 1878 by Auguste Bartholdi that was used to make the statue in New York is in the [[Mus\u00e9e des Arts et M\u00e9tiers]] in Paris.<ref>{{cite book |first1=Robert |last1=Belot |first2=Daniel |last2=Bermond |title=Bartholdi |location=Paris |publisher=\u00c9ditions Perrin |year=2004 |isbn=978-2-26201-991-4}}</ref><ref>E. L. Kallop, Jr., ''Images of Liberty. Models and reductions of the Statue of Liberty 1867\u20131917'', Special Centennial Exhibition 25 Janvier\u201315 F\u00e9vrier 1986</ref> This original plaster was bequeathed by the artist's widow in 1907,<ref>Legal instrument prepared by M. Demanche, notary, on 1 March 1907 (Inv13768ter in the Museum archives).</ref> together with part of the artist's estate.\n\nOn the square outside the Mus\u00e9e des Arts et M\u00e9tiers{{'}}s entrance is a bronze copy made from the plaster maquette, number 1 from an original edition of 12, made by the museum and cast by Susse Fondeur Paris.\n\n====''Flame of Liberty''====\nA life-size copy of the torch, ''[[Flame of Liberty]]'', can be seen above the entrance to the [[Pont de l'Alma]] tunnel near the [[Champs-\u00c9lys\u00e9es]] in Paris. It was given to the city as a return gift in honour of the centennial celebration of the statue's dedication. Since it is above the Pont de l'Alma car tunnel in which [[Princess Diana]] died, the torch became an unofficial memorial to the princess.<ref>{{cite magazine\n|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,624681,00.html\n|title=Paris Honors Diana with Two Memorials\n|date=August 28, 2002\n|first=Stephen M.\n|last=Silverman\n|magazine=[[People (magazine)|People]]}}</ref>\n\n===Barentin===\nThere is a replica in the northwest of France, in the small town of Barentin near [[Rouen]]. It was made for a French movie, ''Le Cerveau'' (\"The Brain\"), directed by G\u00e9rard Oury and featuring actors [[Jean-Paul Belmondo]] and [[Bourvil]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.statueofliberty.info/pages/statue/mondeba.htm |title=Les Statues dans le monde |accessdate=May 28, 2006 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060210152719/http://www.statueofliberty.info/pages/statue/mondeba.htm |archivedate=February 10, 2006 |url-status=dead |df=mdy}}: image and description of the Barentin replica from the personal website of a Statue of Liberty enthusiast.</ref>\n\n===Bordeaux===\nAnother replica is a {{convert|2.5|m|ft|abbr=on}} statue in the city of [[Bordeaux]]. The first Bordeaux statue was seized and melted down by the Nazis in World War II. The statue was replaced in 2000 and a plaque was added to commemorate the victims of the [[September 11, 2001 attacks|11 September terrorist attacks]]. On the night of 25 March 2003, unknown vandals poured red paint and gasoline on the replica and set it on fire. The vandals also cracked the pedestal of the plaque. The mayor of Bordeaux, former prime minister [[Alain Jupp\u00e9]], condemned the attack.\n\n===Colmar===\n[[File:ColmarStatueLibert\u00e9rR\u00e9plique.jpg|thumb|Replica of the Statue of Liberty in [[Colmar]]]]\nA {{convert|12|m|ftin|abbr=on}} replica of the Statue of Liberty in [[Colmar]], the city of [[Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Bartholdi|Bartholdi's]] birth, was dedicated on 4 July 2004, to commemorate the 100th anniversary of his death. It stands at the north entrance of the city.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.endex.com/gf/buildings/liberty/worldstatues/liberties/Colmar/LibertyColmar.htm |title=Statue of Freedom, Colmar, Alsace, France, Birthplace of Auguste Bartholdi |first=Gary |last=Feuerstein |website=endex.com |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100615191834/http://www.endex.com/gf/buildings/liberty/worldstatues/liberties/Colmar/LibertyColmar.htm |archivedate=June 15, 2010}}</ref> The Bartholdi Museum in Colmar contains numerous models of various sizes made by Bartholdi during the process of designing the statue.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cr.nps.gov/history/online_books/hh/11/hh11e.htm |title=Construction of the Statue |date=September 25, 2000 |website=National Park Service Historical Handbook |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604150524/http://www.cr.nps.gov/history/online_books/hh/11/hh11e.htm |archivedate=June 4, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Saint-Cyr-sur-Mer===\nFr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Bartholdi donated a copy of the Statue of Liberty to the town square of [[Saint-Cyr-sur-Mer]].\n\n===Other French cities===\nOther ''Liberty Enlightening the World'' statues are displayed in [[Poitiers]] and [[Lunel]]. The [[Mus\u00e9e des beaux-arts de Lyon]] owns a terracotta version.\n\nNear [[Chaumont, Haute Marne]], is a miniature replica in the flag plaza of the former [[Chaumont Air Base]]. This was the home of the US 48th Tactical Fighter Wing, now based at Lakenheath, England, with its own statue at the flag plaza. The 48th TFW is the only USAF wing with a name: \"The Statue of Liberty Wing\".\n\nAnother example is of a ''Liberty Enlightening the World'' replica in [[Ch\u00e2teauneuf-la-For\u00eat]], near the city of [[Limoges]] in the area of [[Haute-Vienne]], [[Limousin (region)|Limousin]]. There is another \"original\" Bartholdi replica at [[Roybon]] (near Grenoble)\n\nThere is a small replica on [[Promenade des Anglais]] in [[Nice]].\n\n==Other European countries==\n===Austria===\nIn [[Minimundus]], a [[miniature park]] located at the [[W\u00f6rthersee]] in [[Carinthia (state)|Carinthia]], Austria, is another replica of the Statue of Liberty.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.minimundus.at/img/bildarchiv/ba_10_gross.jpg |title=Minimundus replica |website=minimundus.at |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070317230345/http://www.minimundus.at/img/bildarchiv/ba_10_gross.jpg |archivedate=March 17, 2007}}</ref>\n\nIn Graz, standing between the [[Graz Opera|Opera House]] and the NextLiberty Theater, stands a steel structure built out of steel beams, that depict the original size of the statue of liberty, before the plates of the final form were being put into place. Instead of torch of flame, this depiction is holding a sword in extended left arm and a sphere in the right arm representing the world.\n\n===Denmark===\nA small replica in lego is situated in [[Legoland Billund Resort|Legoland]] in [[Billund, Denmark|Billund]].\n\n===Germany===\nA {{convert|35|m|ft|abbr=on}} copy is in the German ''[[Heide Park|Heidepark Soltau]]'' theme park, located on a lake with cruising Mississippi steamboats. It weighs 28 metric tons (31 short tons), is made of plastic foam on a steel frame with polyester cladding, and was designed by the Dutch artist Gerla Spee.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.heidepark.de/swf/assets/parkplan.jpg |title=Freizeitpark und Familienpark in Soltau |website=Heide Park Resort |accessdate=August 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Ireland===\nA green painted replica of the Statue of Liberty can be found near Mulnamina More, [[County Donegal]], Ireland.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.flickriver.com/photos/70302078@N00/3140281654 |title=Flickriver Photo |website=Flickriver.com |date=August 15, 2004 |accessdate=March 19, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Kosovo===\nA replica stands atop the Hotel Victory in [[Pristina]], Kosovo.<ref>{{cite news |last=Smith |first=Morgan |title=Investors should take a closer look at Kosovo |newspaper=[[Denver Business Journal]] |date=July 25, 2003|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/denver/stories/2003/07/28/editorial4.html |quote=It was quite a change to arrive in Pristina, where the main street is named after Bill Clinton and my hotel, the Hotel Victory, has a replica of the Statue of Liberty built on its rooftop.}}</ref>\n\n=== Netherlands ===\n[[File:Drents Vrijheidsbeeld.jpg|thumb|Replica of the Statue of Liberty in [[Assen]], the Netherlands]]\nA 33&nbsp;ft (10 m) replica has its temporary location in the Dutch city of [[Assen]]. The statue bears characteristic features that represent the culture and landscape of the region, like a can of beans instead of the original torch. The replica, by sculptor Natasja Bennink, was on display for the duration of an exhibition on American Realism in the [[Drents Museum]] until 27 May 2018.\n\n===Norway===\nA smaller replica is in the Norwegian village of [[Visnes, Rogaland|Visnes]], where the copper used in the original statue was mined.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.olavsrosa.no/en/objektinfo.aspx?id=27787 |title=Vigsnes Mining Field |website=Olavsrosa.no |date=July 28, 2007 |accessdate=March 19, 2012}}</ref> A replica is also on the facade of a pub in [[Bleik]], county of [[Nordland]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nesthus.net/index.php?p=foto&l=en&bid=Array&bi=262 |title=Nesthus |website=nesthus.net |accessdate=August 1, 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201181543/http://nesthus.net/index.php?p=foto&l=en&bid=Array&bi=262 |archivedate=February 1, 2014 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.bt.no/reise/Pa-spontanferie-mellom-himmel-og-hav-1780575.html#.UuEZm4Y1hFk |title=P\u00e5 spontanferie mellom himmel og hav |first=Christina |last=Pletten |date=July 12, 2010 |newspaper=[[Bergens Tidende]] |language=Norwegian |accessdate=August 1, 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150113130258/http://www.bt.no/reise/Pa-spontanferie-mellom-himmel-og-hav-1780575.html#.UuEZm4Y1hFk |archivedate=January 13, 2015 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Spain===\n[[File:Estatua de la libertad en Cadaqu\u00e9s - de cerca - panoramio.jpg|thumb|left|Replica of the Statue of Liberty in [[Cadaqu\u00e9s]], Spain]]\n* In 1897 a {{convert|123|cm|ftin|abbr=on}} replica in iron and bronze was erected in [[Cenicero]], Spain, to honor local fighters during the [[First Carlist War]]. In 1936 it was removed during [[Spain under Franco|the dictatorship of Francisco Franco]]. It was restored in 1976.\n* The {{ill|Rossend Ar\u00fas public library|ca|Biblioteca P\u00fablica Ar\u00fas|vertical-align=sup}} in [[Barcelona]] has in its entrance a {{convert|2|m|ftin|abbr=on}} replica from 1894. She welcomes visitors to the library, which is devoted to the [[labour movement]], [[anarchism]], and [[freemasonry]].\n* [[Cadaqu\u00e9s]], a small village that was residence of [[Salvador Dal\u00ed]], has an unusual version, with both hands up. It is on top of a small tourism information office.\n\n===Ukraine===\nThere is a unique \"sitting\" Statue of Liberty in the [[Ukraine|Ukrainian]] city of [[Lviv]]. It is a sculpture on a dome of the house (15, Freedom Avenue) built by architect Yuriy Zakharevych and decorated by sculptor [[Leandro Marconi]] in 1874\u201391.\n\n===United Kingdom===\n[[File:Statue of Liberty Leicester UK.jpg|thumb|Replica of the Statue of Liberty in [[Leicester, England]]]]\nA {{convert|17|ft|m|abbr=on}}, 9,200&nbsp;kg (9.2 tons) replica stood atop the Liberty Shoe factory in [[Leicester]], England, until 2002 when the building was demolished. The statue was put into storage while the building was replaced. The statue, which dates back to the 1920s, was initially going to be put back on the replacement building, but was too heavy, so in December 2008 following restoration, it was placed on a pedestal near Liberty Park Halls of Residence on a traffic island, \"Liberty Circus\", close to where it originally stood.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/leicestershire/7478419.stm |title=Landmark could return to skyline |date=June 27, 2008 |website=BBC News |accessdate=August 1, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.leicester.gov.uk/newssite/index01.asp?pgid=8903 |title=Work begins on replacing statue |date=November 20, 2008 |website=Leicester City Council |accessdate=August 1, 2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081227051726/http://www.leicester.gov.uk/newssite/index01.asp?pgid=8903 |archivedate=December 27, 2008}}</ref>\n\nA {{convert|10|ft|m|adj=mid|-high}} replica is in the stairwell of a bowling alley building in Warrington, England. It used to be above the entrance of a restaurant nearby.\n\nThere is also a small replica located at [[RAF Lakenheath]], England, at the base flag plaza, made from leftover copper from the original.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lakenheath.af.mil/shared/media/document/AFD-070730-006.pdf |title=Press release |page=4 |website=lakenheath.af.mil}}{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\n==North America==\n\n===Canada===\nIn [[Coquitlam]], [[British Columbia]] a small replica stands on Delestre Avenue just east of North Road.<ref>{{cite web |title=Statue of Liberty replica in Coquitlam, BC on Google Street View |url=https://www.google.ca/maps/@49.2423537,-122.8919028,3a,75y,33.39h,88.12t/data=!3m6!1e1!3m4!1sQXBS89jbWzou5rL1mmQSpw!2e0!7i13312!8i6656!6m1!1e1?hl=en |accessdate=December 20, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Steinbach, Manitoba]], There will be a construction of the replica of the Statue of Liberty in Southland Park on July 4, 2020.\n\n===Mexico===\n* In [[Campeche]], Mexico, there is a small replica in the small town of [[Palizada]].\n* In [[Durango]], Mexico, a small replica is in Parque Guadiana. This park also has other small reproductions such as the [[Eiffel Tower]] and [[Taj Mahal]].\n\n===United States===\n{{See also|Strengthen the Arm of Liberty}}\n\n* From 1902 to 2002, visitors to midtown Manhattan were occasionally disoriented by what seemed to be an impossibly nearby view of the statue. They were seeing a {{convert|30|ft|m|adj=mid|-high}} replica located at 43 West 64th Street atop the Liberty Warehouse.<ref name=\"BrooklynMuseum\">{{cite web |title=Exhibitions: Replica of the Statue of Liberty: Other Statue of Liberty Replicas |website=Brooklyn Museum |url=http://www.brooklynmuseum.org/exhibitions/statue_of_liberty/ |accessdate=February 17, 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080124100241/http://www.brooklynmuseum.org/exhibitions/statue_of_liberty/ |archivedate=January 24, 2008 |url-status=dead |df=mdy}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.forgotten-ny.com/STREET%20SCENES/STATUE/liberty.html |title=Little Liberty |website=Forgotten New York |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604220808/http://www.forgotten-ny.com/STREET%20SCENES/STATUE/liberty.html |archivedate=June 4, 2011}}</ref> In February 2002, the statue was removed by the building's owners to allow the building to be expanded.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.endex.com/gf/buildings/liberty/worldstatues/.%5Cliberties%5Csol64.htm |title=Statue of Liberty \u2014 Liberty Warehouse |first=Gary |last=Feuerstein |website=endex.com |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081015032723/http://www.endex.com/gf/buildings/liberty/worldstatues/liberties/sol64.htm |archivedate=October 15, 2008 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> It was donated to the Brooklyn Museum of Art, which installed it in its sculpture garden in October 2005 with plans to restore it on site in spring of 2006.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.brooklynmuseum.org/press/pr/2005_08_statue_of_liberty.pdf |title=Brooklyn Museum to Install Monumental Statue of Liberty Replica |website=Brooklyn Museum |date=August 2005 |accessdate=1 August 2005 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060304055325/http://www.brooklynmuseum.org/press/pr/2005_08_statue_of_liberty.pdf |archivedate=March 4, 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.brooklynmuseum.org/press/pr/2005_NovDec_Whats_Happ |title=What's Happening November\u2013December 2005 |website=Brooklyn Museum |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060218142707/http://www.brooklynmuseum.org/press/pr/2005_NovDec_Whats_Happ |archivedate=February 18, 2006}}</ref>\n* A bronze sculpture of the Statue of Liberty is on display in the Metropolitan Museum of Art in New York City.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.insecula.com/oeuvre/O0016026.html/ |title=Statue de la Libert\u00e9: El\u00e9ment 1 sur 11 |website=Insecula.com |accessdate=June 1, 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060509082947/http://www.insecula.com/oeuvre/O0016026.html |archivedate=May 9, 2006 |df=mdy}}</ref>\n* [[Duluth, Minnesota]], has a small copy on the south corner of the Duluth Entertainment Convention Center property, in the center of a clearing surrounded by pine trees where it may be passed unnoticed. It was presented to the city by some of Bartholdi's descendants residing in Duluth.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ci.duluth.mn.us/city/artscommission/otherpublicart.htm |title=Other Public Art |website=City of Duluth |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080624012727/http://www.ci.duluth.mn.us/city/artscommission/otherpublicart.htm |archivedate=June 24, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.geocaching.com/seek/log.aspx?IID=109677de-7cf1-444a-a51b-d53f970cb5d2&LID=9353315 |title=Photograph of Duluth replica |website=geocaching.com}}</ref>\n* The [[Boy Scouts of America]] celebrated their fortieth anniversary in 1950 with the theme of \"[[Strengthen the Arm of Liberty]]\".<ref>{{cite journal |title=Little Sisters of Liberty |journal=Scouting |date=October 2007 |last=Attoun |first=Marti |url=http://www.scoutingmagazine.org/issues/0710/d-wwas.html |accessdate=October 9, 2007}}</ref> Between 1949 and 1952, approximately two hundred {{convert|100|in|m|adj=on}} replicas of the statue, made of stamped copper, were purchased by Boy Scout troops and donated in 39 states in the U.S. and several of its possessions and territories. The project was the brainchild of Kansas City businessman J.P. Whitaker, who was then Scout Commissioner of the [[Kansas City Area Council]]. The copper statues were manufactured by Friedley-Voshardt Co. (Chicago, Illinois) and purchased through the Kansas City Boy Scout office by those wanting one. The statues are approximately {{convert|8+1/2|ft|m}} tall without the base, are constructed of sheet copper, weigh {{convert|290|lb|kg}}, and originally cost $350 plus freight. The mass-produced statues are not great art nor meticulously accurate (a conservator notes that \"her face isn't as mature as the real Liberty. It's rounder and more like a little girl's\"), but they are cherished, particularly since [[September 11, 2001 attacks|9/11]]. Many have been lost or destroyed, but preservationists have been able to account for about a hundred of them, and BSA Troop 101 of Cheyenne, Wyoming, has collected photographs of over 100 of them.<ref>{{cite web |last=Attoun |first=Marti |title=Restoring the Little Sisters of Lady Liberty |url=http://www.americanprofile.com/article/3455.html |website=American Profile |date=September 29, 2007 |accessdate=September 30, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080316155830/http://www.americanprofile.com/article/3455.html |archivedate=March 16, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cheyennetroop101.org/liberty/ |title=Photos and locations of more than ninety of the replicas |website=BSA Troop 101 |location=Cheyenne, Wyoming |accessdate=August 1, 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110910092649/http://www.cheyennetroop101.org/liberty/ |archivedate=September 10, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> They are commonly installed at city halls, libraries, and schools. One of these statues was sent to the Philippines. After some years at the mouth of the Pasig River, Manila, it was kept in a store room at the Scout Reservation, Makiling, Laguna, for about two decades. It is now stored at the national office of the [[Boy Scouts of the Philippines]], Manila.\n*A nine-foot-tall replica of the Statue, built in 1950, stands in [[Warner Park]] in [[Madison, Wisconsin]].<ref name=\"StatueSOS\">{{cite web | author= | year=1993 | title=Statue of Liberty Replica, (sculpture). | work=Save Outdoor Sculpture! | publisher=Inventories of American Painting and Sculpture | url=http://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?&profile=all&source=~!siartinventories&uri=full=3100001~!328309~!0#focus | accessdate= 19 May 2011 }}</ref>\n* A replica of the original statue was unveiled on 12 October 2011, at 667 Madison Avenue in [[Manhattan]]. Its owner, billionaire [[Leonard N. Stern]], purchased it after reading about it in the local news. The replica is one of only 12 cast from the original mold created by [[Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Auguste Bartholdi]] using digital surface scanning and [[lost-wax casting]] methods, and is the only one currently on public display. The statue itself is 9 feet tall and 15 feet including the pedestal on which it stands.<ref>{{cite news |last=Kusisto |first=Laura |title=A New Lady Liberty Lands |newspaper=[[Wall Street Journal]] |date=October 12, 2011 |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052970203633104576625443852552376}}</ref>\n[[File:NYNY2010.JPG|right|thumb|[[New York-New York Hotel & Casino]] in Las Vegas, complete with Statue of Liberty in the foreground.]]\n* There is a half-size replica at the [[New York-New York Hotel & Casino]] in [[Las Vegas, Nevada]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nynyhotelcasino.com/pages/hotel.asp |title=New York, New York Hotel and Casino, Las Vegas |website=nynyhotelcasino.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060613171612/http://www.nynyhotelcasino.com/pages/hotel.asp |archivedate=June 13, 2006 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Levine |first=Arthur |title=Don't Make Mine Manhattan: The Big Apple Roller Coaster at New York New York Casino Hotel |date=February 24, 2016 |url=http://themeparks.about.com/cs/lasvegas/fr/manhattanexpres.htm |work=themeparks.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.virtualtourist.com/travel/North_America/United_States_of_America/Nevada/Las_Vegas-836630/Things_To_Do-Las_Vegas-New_York_New_York-BR-1.html |title=New York, Las Vegas \u2013 Things to Do |website=VirtualTourist |accessdate=July 31, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111123045050/http://www.virtualtourist.com/travel/North_America/United_States_of_America/Nevada/Las_Vegas-836630/Things_To_Do-Las_Vegas-New_York_New_York-BR-1.html |archivedate=November 23, 2011 |df=mdy}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://users.tinyworld.co.uk/mrt/html/ht_nyny.htm |title=New York New York |website=Vegas Views |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060206082524/http://users.tinyworld.co.uk/mrt/html/ht_nyny.htm |archivedate=February 6, 2006}}</ref> In April 2011, the U.S. Postal Service announced that three billion postage stamps mistakenly based on a photograph of this replica were produced and would be sold to the public.<ref name=\"stamperror-reuters\">{{cite news |last=Allen |first=Jonathan |agency=Reuters |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/04/18/uk-usa-stamp-liberty-idUSLNE73H01S20110418 |title=Statue of Liberty postage stamp shows Las Vegas |date=April 11, 2011 |accessdate =April 11, 2011}}</ref> In November 2013, the statue's sculptor, Robert Davidson, filed a copyright infringement suit against the U.S. government.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://nypost.com/2013/12/03/sculptor-sues-postal-service-over-fake-liberty-stamp/ |title=Sculptor sues Postal Service over \"fake Liberty\" stamp |newspaper=[[The New York Post]] |date=December 3, 2013 |accessdate=December 3, 2013}}</ref>\n* Another small replica exists in Las Vegas on Route 589 near Arville St in a plaza parking lot. \n* The city of [[Sioux Falls, South Dakota|Sioux Falls]], South Dakota, erected a replacement bronze reproduction standing {{convert|9|ft|m|abbr=on}} tall in McKennan Park atop the original pedestal of a long-vanished wooden replica.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.siouxfalls.org/Parks/News/2002/July/StatueofLibertyUnveiling.aspx |title=Statue of Liberty unveiling |website=Sioux Falls Parks and Recreation |date=July 2002 }}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n[[File:Liberty Enlightening the Parkway.jpg|thumb|200px|''Liberty Enlightening the World'' replica in [[Birmingham, Alabama|Birmingham]], Alabama]]\n* A {{convert|36|ft|m|adj=mid|-tall}} bronze replica, accurately based on [[Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Bartholdi|Bartholdi's]] ''Liberty Enlightening the World'', stands in [[Vestavia Hills, Alabama|Vestavia Hills]], a suburb of [[Birmingham, Alabama]]. It was cast in 1956 at the ''Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 Antoine Durenne'' foundry in Somerville, Haut Marne, France, for placement in 1958 atop the [[Liberty National Life Insurance Company]] building in downtown Birmingham.<ref name=\"BrooklynMuseum\"/> It was relocated and placed on a {{convert|60|ft|m|adj=mid|-tall}} granite pedestal adjacent to [[Interstate 459]] in 1989.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bhamonline.com/liberty/ |title=Birmingham's Statue of Liberty |website=Birmingham Online.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060829081729/http://www.bhamonline.com/liberty/ |archivedate=August 29, 2006 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"GAStudio\">{{cite web |title=Liberty Statue |website=GA Architecture Studio |url=http://www.gastudio.com/oddlots/10_missliberty/index.html |accessdate=February 17, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090106191555/http://www.gastudio.com/oddlots/10_missliberty/index.html |archivedate=January 6, 2009 |df=mdy}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |website=Roadside America |url=http://www.roadsideamerica.com/tips/getAttraction.php3?tip_AttractionNo==13 |title=Birmingham, Alabama \u2013 Statue of Liberty Replica}}</ref>\n* Two {{convert|30|ft|m|adj=on}} copper replicas by sculptor [[Leo Lentelli]] stand atop the Liberty National Bank Building<ref name=\"BrooklynMuseum\"/> in [[Buffalo, New York]], nearly {{convert|108|m|ft|abbr=on}} above street level.<ref>{{cite web |title=Liberty Building |url=http://www.emporis.com/en/wm/bu/?id=126216 |website=Emporis}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Buffalo \u2013 Liberty Building |url=http://www.planetware.com/buffalo/liberty-building-us-ny-lib.htm |website=PlanetWare}}</ref>\n* A {{convert|25|ft|m|adj=mid|-tall}} replica sits on the ruins of the late [[Marysville Bridge]] (erected on a platform (pier)) in the Dauphin Narrows of [[Susquehanna River]] north of [[Harrisburg]]. The replica was built by a local activist [[Gene Stilp]] on July 2, 1986; it was made of Venetian blinds and stood {{convert|18|ft|m}} tall. Six years later, after it was destroyed in a windstorm, it was rebuilt by Stilp and other local citizens, of wood, metal, glass and fiberglass, to a height of {{convert|25|ft|m}}.<ref>{{cite news |last=Scolforo |first=Mark |year=2004 |url=http://www.phillyburbs.com/pb-dyn/news/103-02142004-246490.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20080108084232/http://www.phillyburbs.com/pb-dyn/news/103-02142004-246490.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=2008-01-08 |title=Master of props lends visual effects to memorable publicity campaigns |agency=Associated Press }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |website=U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service |url=http://www.fish.state.pa.us/watertrails/susqmid/trailguide.htm |title=Susquehanna River Trail: Dauphin Narrows/Statue of Liberty}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.facstaff.bucknell.edu/kochel/classes/susqriver/august31.htm |first=R. Craig |last=Kochel |title=Photograph of the Stilp statue |website=Facstaff.bucknell.edu |date= |accessdate=March 19, 2012}}</ref>\n* A [[Lego]] replica of the Statue of Liberty consisting of 2882 bricks and standing {{convert|0.9|m|ft|abbr=on}} is a popular sculpture among Lego enthusiasts. The statue went out of production, but due to popular demand was returned to sale.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.roadsideamerica.com/story/10907 |title=Statue of Liberty Sculpture (#3450-1) |website=RoadSide America |date= |accessdate=July 31, 2012}}</ref>\n* A 1/12 replica of the Statue of Liberty made essentially out of junk stands at the intersection of [[US 280]] and [[US 341]] in [[McRae, Georgia]]. The head is made out of a stump from a nearby swamp, the arm holding the torch is made from [[styrofoam]] and the hand holding the book is actually an electric lineman's glove. The town's [[Lion's Club]] erected the replica in 1986 during the statue's centennial.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.roadsideamerica.com/story/10907 |title=Home-Built Statue of Liberty Replica |website=RoadSide America |date= |accessdate=May 31, 2017}}</ref>\n* An {{convert|11|ft|m|adj=on}} miniature Statue of Liberty (holding a Bible instead of a tablet) currently stands atop a {{convert|15|ft|m|adj=on}} pedestal outside the Liberty Recycling plant in [[San Marcos, California]]. The company was named after the statue, which has been moved throughout [[San Diego North County|northern San Diego County]] for over 80 years, originating at the Liberty Hotel in [[Encinitas, California|Leucadia]], in the 1920s.<ref>{{cite news |newspaper=[[North County Times]] |url=http://www.nctimes.com/news/local/article_4dd6b10d-d720-546e-85f9-69ac5553c1b0.html |title=Lady Liberty lowered in San Marcos |access-date=October 17, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100523160736/http://www.nctimes.com/news/local/article_4dd6b10d-d720-546e-85f9-69ac5553c1b0.html |archive-date=May 23, 2010 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n* A {{convert|25|ft|m|adj=on}} replica of the statue, lofting a Christian cross, holding the Ten Commandments, and named the ''Statue of Liberation through Christ'', was erected by a predominantly African American church in [[Memphis, Tennessee]], on 4 July 2006.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thestatueofliberationthroughchrist.org/ |title=Home |website=thestatueofliberationthroughchrist.org}}</ref>\n* A small replica stands on the grounds of the [[Cherokee]] Capitol Building in [[Tahlequah, Oklahoma]], a gift from the local [[Scouting in Oklahoma|Boy Scouts]] in 1950 (presumably as part of the above-mentioned national Boy Scout celebration).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lasr.net/leisure/oklahoma/cherokee/tahlequah/att3f.html |title=Statue of Liberty Replica |website=Leisure and Sport Review |year=2006 |accessdate=October 7, 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060904193624/http://www.lasr.net/leisure/oklahoma/cherokee/tahlequah/att3f.html |archive-date=September 4, 2006 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n* [[Fargo, North Dakota]], also had a replica of the Statue of Liberty on the corner of Main Avenue and 2nd Street at the entrance of the Main Avenue bridge, which was reported stolen on July 26th, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kfgo.com/news/articles/2019/jul/27/fargos-statue-of-liberty-stolen-no-questions-no-charges-if-its-returned/922028/|title=Fargo's Statue of Liberty stolen - no questions, no charges if it's returned|last=Inc|first=Midwest Communications|website=The Mighty 790 KFGO|access-date=2019-08-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |website=Digital Horizons |title=Statue of Liberty replica, Fargo, N.D. |url=http://digitalhorizonsonline.org/cdm/ref/collection/uw/id/5888 |accessdate=14 December 2014}}</ref>\n* There is a replica on the shoreline of [[Lake Chaubunagungamaug]] in [[Webster, Massachusetts]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Belluck |first=Pam |title=What's the Name of That Lake? It's Hard to Say |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=November 20, 2004 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/11/20/national/20lake.html}}</ref>\n* A 1/6-scale replica (\u224850 feet including pedestal) stands in a parking lot of a strip mall in [[Milwaukie, Oregon]], off McLoughlin Blvd at 4255 SE Roethe Rd.<ref>{{cite web |website=Roadside America |url=http://www.roadsideamerica.com/tip/15118 |title=Milwaukee, OR Statue of Liberty Replica}}</ref>\n* A {{convert|6|ft|adj=on}} replica stands at [[Statue of Liberty (Seattle)|Statue of Liberty Plaza]] in [[West Seattle]], Washington, at [[Alki Beach Park]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kuow.org/post/seattles-tiny-statue-liberty-0 |title=Seattle's Tiny Statue of Liberty |first=Joshua |last=McNichols |website=kuow.org |accessdate=August 1, 2017}}</ref>\n* A replica of the Statue of Liberty stands on [[Mackinac Island]], [[Michigan]].<ref>https://bree1972.wordpress.com/2013/09/12/lady-liberty-returns-to-mackinac-island/</ref>\n* A replica of the Statue of Liberty is located in the downtown area of New Castle, Pennsylvania.<ref name=\"visitlawrencecounty.com\">https://www.visitlawrencecounty.com/local-attractions/featured-attractions/statues-of-liberty/</ref>\n* A replica of the Statue of Liberty is located near the Lincoln High School in Ellwood City, Pennsylvania.<ref name=\"visitlawrencecounty.com\"/>\n* A bronze replica of the Statue of Liberty resides in Neenah, WI. It was cast in California by the Great American Bronze Works. This version of the Statue of Liberty is 14 feet, 6 inches tall. It is 10 percent the size of the original.<ref>http://www.waymarking.com/waymarks/WMCYYB_Statue_of_Liberty_Neenah_WI</ref><ref>http://www.bronzeking.com/Gallery/Sculptures/Monumentals/StatueOfLiberty.html</ref>\n* A replica approximately the same size as an adult person is located alongside Highway 80 at the west end of [[Forney, Texas]].  An earlier installation stood from 1986 until May 2016, when it was removed to make way for highway construction.  As of November, 2019, it has been replaced in nearly the same spot, this time painted a darker green and with a illuminated torch.<ref>https://www.inforney.com/local-news/construction-underway-to-replace-forney-s-replica-statue-of-liberty/article_bd8c9840-d044-11e9-96c8-eb05b4cfbc74.html</ref>\n\nIn Lake Michigan campground in [[Wisconsin]], There will be a new sculpture park, The first artifact will be the Statue of Liberty, It will be designed by many architects from [[New York]], [[Pennsylvania]], [[Florida]], [[France]], [[Minnesota]], and of course, Wisconsin, It will be under construction on June 5, 2020.\n\n==South America==\n===Argentina===\nIn [[Buenos Aires]] there is a small iron replica in Barrancas de Belgrano Square, cast by Bartholdi from the same mould as those cast in Paris; although it is much smaller. It was inaugurated on 3 October 1886, 25 days before the one in New York. Another replica was bought by the government and placed in a school, Colegio Nacional Sarmiento, about the same date.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://turismo.perfil.com/18897-un-paseo-por-la-estatua-de-la-libertad-y-sus-hermanas-gemelas/ |title=Un paseo por la Estatua de la Libertad (y sus hermanas gemelas) |date=May 31, 2013 |newspaper=[[Perfil]] |accessdate=August 1, 2017}}</ref> There is another replica in Plaza Libertad (Liberty Square) in the city of [[Villa Aberastain]], [[San Juan Province, Argentina|San Juan]]. This one arrived at the city in 1909 due to a confusion since it had to be shipped to San Juan, Puerto Rico instead. There are also two cheaper non-metallic replicas; one is 6 m tall, located in the \"New York\" Casino in [[San Luis, Argentina|San Luis]] and the other crowns a commercial gallery, \"Galer\u00eda de Fabricantes\", in [[Munro]], a city in the northeast suburbs of Buenos Aires.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.taringa.net/posts/info/17176133/La-estatua-de-la-libertad-argentina.html |title=La Estatua de la Libertad, Argentina |website=taringa.net |accessdate=August 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Brazil===\n[[File:2010-10-30 replica Statue of Liberty Maceio Alagoas Brazil.JPG|thumb|A replica of the [[Statue of Liberty]] in [[Macei\u00f3]], Alagoas, Brazil]]\n[[File:Barra.100.jpg|thumb|New York City Center in [[Rio de Janeiro]], Brazil]]\nIn [[Bangu, Rio de Janeiro]] exists a [[nickel]] replica made by [[Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Auguste Bartholdi|Bartholdi]] in 1899. Bartholdi was commissioned by [[Jos\u00e9 Paranhos, Baron of Rio Branco]] to make a replica in order to celebrate the 10th anniversary of the [[Brazil|Republic of Brazil]]. Until 1940, the statue was Paranhos family property. In 1940 the statue was passed to [[Guanabara State]]. In 20 January 1964 [[Carlos Lacerda]], governor of [[Guanabara State]], placed the statue in Miami Square, [[Bangu, Rio de Janeiro|Bangu]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blogdaalessandravieira.blogspot.com/2011/11/historia-de-que-estatua-da-liberdade.html |first=Alessandra |last=Vieira |title=Historia de que estatua da liberdade |date=November 2011 |website=Blogspot.com |accessdate=August 1, 2017}}</ref>\n{{Coord|-22.856681 |-43.492577}}\n\nA small-scale cast metal replica can be found in [[Macei\u00f3]], the capital of [[Alagoas]] State, in northeast Brazil. The replica is in front of a building constructed in 1869 as the seat of the ''Conselho Provincial'' (Provincial Council), and which today is the Museu da Imagem e do Som de Alagoas (Museum of Image and Sound of Alagoas). This replica is possibly a casting produced by the {{ill|Fundi\u00e7\u00e3o Val d'Osne|pt|Fundi\u00e7\u00e3o Val d'Osne|vertical-align=sup}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.revistadehistoria.com.br/v2/home/?go=detalhe&id=2341 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120914094154/http://www.revistadehistoria.com.br/v2/home/?go=detalhe&id=2341 |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 14, 2012 |title=Quando o ferro virou arte |website=Revista de Hist\u00f3ria |date=December 4, 2009 |accessdate=July 31, 2012}}</ref> in France, as in the Pra\u00e7a Lavenere Machado (formerly Pra\u00e7a Dois Le\u00f5es) on the opposite side of the museum, there are four somewhat larger-than-life size cast metal statues of wild animals, at least one of which is embossed with the name of the foundry. These castings and the replica all appear to be made of similar material and to be of similar age. It is also probable that they are near contemporaries of the actual Statue of Liberty.\n{{Coord|-9.6728563|-35.7223114}}\n\nA large modern replica stands in front of the New York City Center, a shopping center constructed in 1999 in [[Barra da Tijuca]] in the [[Rio de Janeiro (state)|State of Rio de Janeiro]].\n{{Coord|-22.9992837|-43.360481}}\n\nThe Havan department store chain has replicas in many of their stores. The largest one of these, 57 meters tall,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://folha1.blogspot.com.br/2012/10/conheca-as-5-maiores-estatuas-do-brasil.html |title=Conhe\u00e7a as 5 Maiores Est\u00e1tuas do Brasil |author=Guilherme |date=October 2012 |website=blogspot.com.br |accessdate=August 1, 2017}}</ref> is allegedly in the [[Barra Velha]] branc, in the state of [[Santa Catarina (state)|Santa Catarina]].{{Coord|-26.635870|-48.698708}} There is another large replica the parking area of a Havan Department Store on the outskirts of [[Curitiba]], in the [[Paran\u00e1 (state)|State of Paran\u00e1]], opened in 2000.\n{{Coord|-25.4639912|-49.2521676}}\n\nAlso, there is a small replica of the statue in [[Bel\u00e9m]], in front of a Bel\u00e9m Importados store, near the city's port.\n\n===Ecuador===\nIn [[Guayaquil]], a little replica gives the name of \"New York\" to a neighborhood in the Valle Alto area.\n\n===Peru===\nIn [[Lima]] the New York Casino in the [[Jes\u00fas Mar\u00eda District, Lima|Jes\u00fas Mar\u00eda District]] has a small replica in the main entrance. The casino is a tribute to the state of New York and the USA.\n\n==Asia==\n===[[India]]===\nA small replica can be found in [[Vardhaman Fantasy]], an amusement park in Mira Road, [[Mumbai]] along with other six [[wonders of the world]].\n\nThe 7 wonders of the world are made in Eco Park, Kolkata, West Bengal\n\nAnother small replica can be found in [[Seven Wonders Park]], a park in Kotri, [[Kota, Rajasthan|Kota]], [[Rajasthan]] along with other six [[wonders of the world]].\n\n===Malaysia===\nA large replica can be found in [[Genting Highlands]] in the state of [[Pahang]].\n\n===Singapore===\nA small replica can be found in [[Haw Par Villa]], a theme park.\n\n===China===\n====Guangzhou====\nSet on top of the memorial tomb of \"72 Martyrs of Huanghuagang\" (see [[Huanghuagang Uprising]]). The current one was re-built in 1981.\n\n====Beijing====\nDuring the [[Tiananmen Square protests of 1989|Tiananmen Square protest of 1989]], Chinese student demonstrators in Beijing built a 10&nbsp;m (33&nbsp;ft) image called the ''[[Goddess of Democracy]]'', which sculptor Tsao Tsing-yuan said was intentionally \"dissimilar\" to the Statue of Liberty to avoid being \"too openly pro-American.\" (See article for a list of replicas of that statue.)\n\n====Shenzhen====\nA replica can be found in [[Window of the World]] Park.\n\n===Israel===\n\nA 15 foot high replica of the Statue of Liberty is at the western entrance of the village of [[Arraba, Galilee|Arraba]] in Israel, near a local restaurant.\n\nAt a highway intersection in [[Jerusalem]] called \"New York Square,\" there is an abstract skeletal replica of the statue.\n\n===Japan===\n\nThe French Statue of Liberty from the [[\u00cele aux Cygnes]] came to [[Odaiba]], [[Tokyo]], from April 1998 to May 1999 in commemoration of \"The French year in Japan\".<ref name=japantimes /> Because of its popularity, in 2000 a replica of the French Statue of Liberty was erected at the same place. Also in Japan, a small Statue of Liberty is in the [[Amerikamura|Amerika-mura]] (''American Village'') shopping district in [[Osaka]], Japan. Another replica is in [[Oirase, Aomori|Oirase]]<ref>{{cite news |last=Osumi |first=Magdalena |url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/culture/2013/09/26/events/events-outside-tokyo/floats-make-oirase-fest-a-treat/ |title=Floats make Oirase fest a treat |date=September 26, 2013 |newspaper=[[Japan Times]] |accessdate=October 4, 2015}}</ref> near the town of [[Shimoda, Aomori|Shimoda]] south of [[Misawa, Aomori|Misawa]] in [[Aomori Prefecture]], where the United States has an 8,000-person [[U.S. Air Force]] base. A replica of the Statue of Liberty in [[Ishinomaki, Miyagi|Ishinomaki, Miyagi Prefecture]], was damaged by the [[2011 T\u014dhoku earthquake and tsunami]].<ref>{{cite news |last=MacLeod |first=Calum |url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/news/world/2011-03-16-japanstruggle16_ST_N.htm |title=Public order still rules amid devastation in Japan |date=March 16, 2011 |newspaper=[[USA Today]] |accessdate=October 4, 2015}}</ref> There is also a replica in [[Oyabe, Toyama|Oyabe]], [[Toyama Prefecture|Toyama]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/%E3%80%92932-0134+Toyama-ken,+Oyabe-shi,+Hirazakura,+%E8%87%AA%E7%94%B1%E3%81%AE%E5%83%8F/@36.8045769,133.3038557,6.8z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x5ff82beb66df6583:0xea33d5b10148d1c6!8m2!3d36.6290409!4d136.8444317|title=Google Maps, \u81ea\u7531\u306e\u50cf, Oyabe Toyama|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n===Pakistan===\nThere are replicas of the Statue of Liberty in [[Bahria Town]], [[Lahore]], and also in [[Bahria Town Phase 8]], [[Islamabad]].\n\n===Philippines===\nAs early as January 1945, there were already news of a campaign that would help erect a Statue of Liberty replica in the [[Philippines]]. The said monument was supposed to be sponsored by The Chicago Daily Times whose goal was \u201cto commemorate one of the great epics in the struggle for human freedom\u2013the liberation of the Philippines.\u201d\n\nFast forward to 1950, the Boy Scouts of America was celebrating its 40th anniversary. Jack P. Whitaker, then Scout Commissioner of the Kansas City Area Council, had earlier suggested the creation and distribution of several Statue of Liberty replicas to all American states and territories, including the Philippines.\n\n[[File:Carlos P. Romulo (on the left) and Arthur A. Shuck.jpg|thumb|Chief Scout Executive Arthur A. Shuck presenting to [[Carlos P. Romulo]] a miniature of the Statue of Liberty in April 1950.]]\n\nThe eight-foot statues, which were cast in bronze, were distributed all over the U.S. and the world from 1949 to 1951. Almost 200 replicas were delivered to the 39 states of the U.S. and countries such as Panama and Puerto Rico. The [[Boy Scouts of the Philippines]], on the other hand, received its own replica in the early part of 1950.\n\nThe statues were donated by the Boy Scouts of America as \u201can expression of scout brotherhood and goodwill.\u201d Not surprisingly, their 40th anniversary theme was \u201cStrengthen the Arm of Liberty.\u201d\n\nMiniature versions of the statue were also given as gifts. In fact, the Philippines became the first independent nation to receive one of the 4,000 eight-inch statues from the Boy Scouts of America. In April 1950, the said statue was officially given by Chief Scout Executive Arthur A. Shuck to [[Carlos P. Romulo]], then chief of the Philippine Mission to the United Nations.\n\nIn the Philippines, several places were suggested as the site where the eight-foot bronze replica would be erected. The task of choosing the perfect site was delegated to the National Urban Planning Commission, and among those it considered were \u201cEngineer Island, atop the proposed reviewing stand on the [[Rizal Park]], and on the center island rotunda between the [[Old Legislative building]] and [[Manila City Hall]].\u201d\n\nIn the end, the [[Boy Scouts of the Philippines]] (BSP) erected the statue just outside [[Intramuros]]. As the icon of the United States, the replica of Lady Liberty would survive several attacks by student protesters in the 1960s. It remained standing until the early 1970s, when the BSP decided to transfer it to the Scout Reservation in [[Mt. Makiling]] which would serve as the statue's home for two decades or so.\n\nIn a 2002 article published by the Philippine Star, then BSP PR head Nixon Canlapan revealed that the Statue of Liberty was eventually moved and stored at the BSP headquarters on Concepcion Street (now Natividad Almeda-Lopez) in Ermita, Manila.\n\nTurns out, the American-sponsored replica was not the first Lady Liberty in [[Manila]]. In the 1930s, one of Manila's biggest shopping stores at that time became the talk of the town not just for its products but also for its unique multi-story building. Located in Juan Luna Street, the L.R. Aguinaldo's Emporium had an Art Deco facade featuring two contrasting statues: [[Andres Bonifacio]] on the right and the Statue of Liberty on the left.\n\n[[File:Souvenir postcard featuring the L.R. Aguinaldo Building in Juan Luna St., Manila.jpg|thumb|Established by the Philippine retailing pioneer Leopoldo R. Aguinaldo, the L.R. Aguinaldo's Emporium was once one of the biggest shopping stores in pre-war Manila, located in Juan Luna Street, Manila. The multi-story building's facade featured a statue of Andres Bonifacio on the right and a replica of the statue of Liberty on the left.]]\n\nEstablished by Philippine retailing pioneer Leopoldo R. Aguinaldo, the store would later become known as the Aguinaldo's Department Store. After the war, Leopoldo's son Francisco took over the business and the store was moved to Echague.\n\nThe Echague branch in the 1950s was known for introducing its customers to quality products both from the Philippines and abroad. It also commissioned young interior designers to update the store's furniture section. Thus, the store catapulted the careers of famous designers like Myra Cruz, Edgar Ramirez, and Bonnie Ramos, among others. Aguinaldo's succumbed to the competition and closed in the 1960s. The original building in Juan Luna Street still stands, along with both the Bonifacio and the Liberty statues.\n\nSince the creation of the Liberty statues in Intramuros and Juan Luna Street, other Philippine provinces soon followed suit. Statue of Liberty replicas in can be found in [[Pangasinan]] and as far as [[Camp John Hay]] amphitheater in [[Baguio City]].\n\n===Thailand===\n\nThe Mini Siam and Mini Europe [[Miniature park|model village]], in [[Pattaya]], has a miniature Statue of Liberty amongst others.\n\n===Taiwan===\nThere are at least two Statue of Liberty replicas (greater than 30 feet in height) in [[Taiwan]]. These two statues are in the cities of [[Keelung]] and [[Taipei]].<ref>{{cite web |author=Sandy H. \u4f55\u8056\u6b23 |url=http://sandyintaiwan.blogspot.com/2007/08/statues-of-liberty.html#links |title=Sandy's Neipu Notebook: Statues of Liberty |website=Blogspot.com |date=August 30, 2007 |accessdate=July 31, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Vietnam===\nFrom 1887 to 1945, [[Hanoi]] was home to another copy of the statue. Measuring {{convert|2.85|m|ftin|abbr=on}} tall, it was erected by the French colonial government after being sent from France for an exhibition. It was known to locals unaware of its history as ''{{ill|T\u01b0\u1ee3ng B\u00e0 \u0111\u1ea7m x\u00f2e|vi|T\u01b0\u1ee3ng b\u00e0 \u0111\u1ea7m x\u00f2e|vertical-align=sup}}'' (''Statue of the madame saux''). When the French lost control of [[French Indochina]] during World War II, the statue was toppled on 1 August 1945, after being deemed a vestige of the colonial government along with other statues erected by the French.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://vietnamnet.vn/thuhanoi/2005/08/474419/ |title=H\u00e0 N\u1ed9i t\u1eebng c\u00f3 t\u01b0\u1ee3ng Th\u1ea7n T\u1ef1 Do tr\u00ean n\u00f3c Th\u00e1p R\u00f9a? |trans-title=Has Hanoi ever had the Statue of Liberty on the roof of the Turtle Tower? |website=Vietnam Net |language=Vietnamese |date=1 August 2005 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060708104847/http://www.vietnamnet.vn/thuhanoi/2005/08/474419/ |archivedate=July 8, 2006 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Australia==\nA 30-foot replica can also be seen at the [[Westfield Marion]] shopping complex in [[Adelaide]], South Australia.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Replicas of the Statue of Liberty}}\n* [http://www.statue-de-la-liberte.com/en/Copies-of-the-statue-of-Liberty.php Statues of Liberty in the world]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110910092649/http://www.cheyennetroop101.org/liberty/ Replica Statue of Liberty Search]\n* [http://architecturalwonder.blogspot.com/2010/07/statue-of-liberty.html Quick view of Statue of Liberty]\n\n{{Statue of Liberty|state=expanded}}\n{{Appropriation in the arts}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Replicas Of The Statue Of Liberty}}\n[[Category:Liberty symbols]]\n[[Category:Lists of replicas]]\n[[Category:Outdoor sculptures]]\n[[Category:Replicas of the Statue of Liberty| ]]\n[[Category:Scale modeling]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toNew York(link changed toNew York (state)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Replicas_of_the_Statue_of_Liberty"}
{"title_page": "Lalo\u0219u", "text_new": "{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = commune\n|county                 = V\u00e2lcea\n|population_total       = auto\n|map_caption            = Location in V\u00e2lcea County\n|name=Lalo\u0219u\n|image_map              = Lalo\u0219u en distrikto V\u00e2lcea.png\n|coordinates = {{coord|44|33|N|24|1|E|region:RO|display=it}}\n}}\n'''Lalo\u0219u''' is a [[Commune in Romania|commune]] located in [[V\u00e2lcea County]], [[Romania]]. It is composed of six villages: Ghindari, Lalo\u0219u, Port\u0103re\u0219ti, Mologe\u0219ti, Berbe\u0219ti and Olte\u021bani.\n\n{{LocalitiesValcea}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lalosu}}\n[[Category:Communes in V\u00e2lcea County]]\n\n{{V\u00e2lcea-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = commune\n|county                 = V\u00e2lcea\n|population_total       = auto\n|map_caption            = Location in V\u00e2lcea County\n|name=Lalo\u0219u\n|image_map=\n|coordinates = {{coord|44|33|N|24|1|E|region:RO|display=it}}\n}}\n'''Lalo\u0219u''' is a [[Commune in Romania|commune]] located in [[V\u00e2lcea County]], [[Romania]]. It is composed of six villages: Ghindari, Lalo\u0219u, Port\u0103re\u0219ti, Mologe\u0219ti, Berbe\u0219ti and Olte\u021bani.\n\n{{LocalitiesValcea}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lalosu}}\n[[Category:Communes in V\u00e2lcea County]]\n\n{{V\u00e2lcea-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Markussep", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lalo%C8%99u"}
{"title_page": "USS Terror (BM-4)", "text_new": "{{other ships|USS Terror}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=[[Image:USS Terror LOC det 4a05511.jpg|300px|USS Terror]]\n|Ship caption=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country=United States\n|Ship flag={{USN flag|1907}}\n|Ship name=USS ''Terror''\n|Ship namesake=\n|Ship ordered=23 June 1874\n|Ship builder=[[William Cramp & Sons]], [[Philadelphia]]\n|Ship yard number=195\n|Ship laid down=1874\n|Ship launched=24 March 1883\n|Ship acquired=\n|Ship commissioned=15 April 1896\n|Ship decommissioned=8 May 1906\n|Ship in service=\n|Ship out of service=\n|Ship struck=31 December 1915\n|Ship reclassified=\n|Ship homeport=\n|Ship motto=\n|Ship nickname=\n|Ship honours=\n|Ship fate=Presumed scrapped, 1930s\n|Ship status=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship type={{sclass-|Amphitrite|monitor|4}} [[Monitor (warship)|monitor]]\n|Ship displacement={{convert|3990|LT|t|0|abbr=on}}\n|Ship length={{convert|263|ft|1|in|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship beam={{convert|55|ft|6|in|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship draft={{convert|14|ft|8|in|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship hold depth=\n|Ship propulsion=[[Steam engine]]\n|Ship sail plan=\n|Ship speed={{convert|12|kn|lk=in}}\n|Ship range=\n|Ship complement=150 officers and enlisted\n|Ship armament=*4 \u00d7 [[10\"/30 caliber gun|{{convert|10|in|mm|abbr=on|0}}/caliber]] breechloader rifles\n* 2 \u00d7 {{convert|4|in|mm|abbr=on}} rifles\n* 2 \u00d7 [[QF 3-pounder Hotchkiss|3-pounder]] guns\n|Ship armor=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n'''USS ''Terror''''' (Monitor No. 4)\u2014the totally rebuilt version of the earlier [[Monitor (warship)|monitor]] {{USS|Agamenticus|1863|2}}, which had shared the ''Terror's'' name\u2014was an iron-hulled, twin-screw, double-turreted [[Monitor (warship)|monitor]] of the {{sclass-|Amphitrite|monitor|4}}; on June 23, 1874 by order of President [[Ulysses S. Grant]]'s Secretary of Navy [[George M. Robeson]] in response to the [[Virginius Incident]] laid down (''scrapped and rebuilt'') at [[Philadelphia]] contracted by [[William Cramp & Sons]]. Her construction progressed over the next three years until suspended in 1877. Work was resumed six years later, and the monitor was launched on 24 March 1883.\n\nDelivered to the [[United States Navy|Navy]] in 1887, the still-unfinished warship was taken to the [[New York Navy Yard]] for completion. Over the next seven years, she fitted out at a leisurely pace. ''Terror'' was finally commissioned at [[New York City]] on 15 April 1896, with [[Captain (United States O-6)|Captain]] Purnell Frederick Harrington in command.\n\n==Service history==\n\n===Spanish\u2013American War===\nAssigned to the [[North Atlantic Squadron]], ''Terror'' operated off the east coast of the [[United States]], from [[Tompkinsville, New York]], to [[Hampton Roads]] and [[Fort Monroe|Fort Monroe, Virginia]]; and from [[Sandy Hook, New Jersey]] to [[Charleston, South Carolina]], through the winter of 1897 and 1898. On 5 May, 1897 she collided with steam [[Yacht]] \"Penelope\"  ({{flag|United States|1891}})  off [[Hoffman Island]], [[New York City|New York]] doing $500 in damage to the Yacht.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=osu.32435066693086&view=1up&seq=32 |page={{#expr:32-6}} |title=Annual report of the Supervising Inspector-general Steamboat-inspection Service, Year ending June 30, 1898 ||location=Washington |publisher=Government Printing Office |date=1897|via=Haithi Trust |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.loc.gov/resource/sn83030180/1897-05-06/ed-1/?sp=7&st=text&r=0.165,0.251,0.521,0.515,0 |title=Image 7 of New York journal and advertiser (New York [N.Y.]), May 6, 1897 |publisher=Library of Congress |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> The mysterious explosion which wrecked the [[armored cruiser]] {{USS|Maine|ACR-1|2}} at [[Havana]] Harbor on 15 February 1898 materially increased tensions between the United States and [[Spain]]. ''Terror'' sped south from Tompkinsville to join the fleet concentrating in southern waters and arrived at [[Key West]] on 2 April 1898.\n\nOn 22 April, after receiving orders from [[President of the United States|President]] [[William McKinley]], [[Rear admiral (United States)|Rear Admiral]] [[William T. Sampson]], commanding the North Atlantic Squadron from {{USS|New York|ACR-2|2}} (Armored Cruiser No. 2), deployed his fleet in preparation for a blockade of the [[Cuba]]n coast. Three days later, the United States [[Declaration of war|declared war]] on Spain, beginning the [[Spanish\u2013American War]]. ''Terror'', which had arrived off [[Cardenas de Cuba|Cardenas, Cuba]], on the 24th, captured a Cuban vessel\u2014''Almansas''\u2014on the first day of hostilities, but later released her. Over the next two days, the monitor took two Spanish ships, ''Ambrosia Bolivar'' and ''Guido'', and sent the prizes to [[Florida]].\n\nMeanwhile, the whereabouts of the Spanish Navy's ''Caribbean Squadron'' under [[Admiral]] [[Pascual Cervera y Topete|Pascual Cervera]] prompted concern in naval circles in [[Washington, D.C.|Washington]]. Intelligence estimates which reached Sampson noted that the Spanish fleet had departed the [[Cape Verde|Cape Verde Islands]] on the morning of 29 April. Sampson reacted by deciding to meet Cervera's fleet at [[San Juan, Puerto Rico]], the nearest Spanish base in the [[Caribbean|West Indies]]. With his flag in ''New York'', Rear Admiral Sampson scraped together a makeshift squadron\u2014which included ''Terror'' and a sistership, {{USS|Amphitrite|1883|2}} (Monitor No. 2), as well as battleships {{USS|Iowa|BB-4|2}} (Battleship No. 4) and {{USS|Indiana|BB-1|2}}  (Battleship No. 1), {{USS|Porter|TB-6|2}} (Torpedo Boat No. 6), two auxiliaries and a collier\u2014and departed Key West on 3 May.\n\n''Terror'' and ''Amphitrite'' broke down frequently en route and materially delayed Sampson's passage. At one point, ''New York'' took both ''Terror'' and ''Porter'' in tow. Upon arrival off San Juan on 12 May, the Americans found only a couple of minor Spanish gunboats in the harbor. In order to \"develop their positions and strength\", Sampson decided to conduct a brief bombardment of the shore defenses. The squadron stood in for their target at 04:00, on 12 May 1898, with the ships cleared for action and the lights of the town clearly visible in the predawn darkness. Sounding general quarters at 05:00, the Americans opened fire within 15 minutes, and the Spanish began returning fire at 05:23.\n\n''Terror'' stood in, fifth in column, duelling with the Spanish shore batteries in a spirited engagement for the next three hours. As the action wore on, a tremendous volume of white smoke restricted visibility and caused the Admiral to signal \"use large guns only\" to cut down on the volume of smoke.\n\n''Terror'' expended thirty-one 10-inch shells in three firing passes against the fortifications at San Juan, and scored a direct hit on a battery which the monitor's commanding officer, Capt. Nicholl Ludlow, considered \"the most vicious\". ''Terror'', which had moved close inshore to gain a better firing position, kept up a spirited fire until 08:15, when she broke off action and rejoined Sampson's squadron retiring to the northwest.\n\nThe monitor subsequently resumed her cruising operations in the West Indies and off Puerto Rico for the duration of hostilities with Spain, into September 1898. At the conclusion of the war, ''Terror'' sailed north for Hampton Roads. Placed in reserve at [[Norfolk, Virginia|Norfolk]] on 18 October 1898, the monitor was decommissioned and placed in ordinary on 25 February 1899.\n\n===Naval Academy ship===\nTaken to [[Annapolis, Maryland]], late in 1901, ''Terror'' was recommissioned for service at the [[United States Naval Academy|Naval Academy]] and subsequently served as a practice ship for [[midshipmen]]. She conducted a summer midshipman cruise in 1905. Later taken up to Philadelphia, ''Terror'' was placed in reserve on 11 September 1905 and was decommissioned and laid up at [[League Island]] on 8 May 1906.\n\n===Fate===\nStruck from the Navy list on 31 December 1915, ''Terror'' lay at [[Indian Head, Maryland]] as a test hulk at the [[Indian Head Naval Surface Weapons Center|Naval Proving Grounds]], before being placed on the sale list in June 1920. Although sold for scrap iron on 10 March 1921, ''Terror'' sank off [[Shooters Island]], New York, sometime in the 1920s. Records indicate that the hulk was raised by the Sorenson Wrecking Company in early 1930, while operating under contract with the Navy. This hulk was presumably scrapped soon thereafter.\n\n==References==\n* {{DANFS|http://www.history.navy.mil/research/histories/ship-histories/danfs/t/terror-ii.html}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Amphitrite class monitor}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Terror (BM-4)}}\n[[Category:Amphitrite-class monitors]]\n[[Category:Ships built by William Cramp & Sons]]\n[[Category:Ships built in Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:1883 ships]]\n[[Category:Spanish\u2013American War monitors of the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{other ships|USS Terror}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=[[Image:USS Terror LOC det 4a05511.jpg|300px|USS Terror]]\n|Ship caption=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country=United States\n|Ship flag={{USN flag|1907}}\n|Ship name=USS ''Terror''\n|Ship namesake=\n|Ship ordered=23 June 1874\n|Ship builder=[[William Cramp & Sons]], [[Philadelphia]]\n|Ship yard number=195\n|Ship laid down=1874\n|Ship launched=24 March 1883\n|Ship acquired=\n|Ship commissioned=15 April 1896\n|Ship decommissioned=8 May 1906\n|Ship in service=\n|Ship out of service=\n|Ship struck=31 December 1915\n|Ship reclassified=\n|Ship homeport=\n|Ship motto=\n|Ship nickname=\n|Ship honours=\n|Ship fate=Presumed scrapped, 1930s\n|Ship status=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship type={{sclass-|Amphitrite|monitor|4}} [[Monitor (warship)|monitor]]\n|Ship displacement={{convert|3990|LT|t|0|abbr=on}}\n|Ship length={{convert|263|ft|1|in|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship beam={{convert|55|ft|6|in|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship draft={{convert|14|ft|8|in|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship hold depth=\n|Ship propulsion=[[Steam engine]]\n|Ship sail plan=\n|Ship speed={{convert|12|kn|lk=in}}\n|Ship range=\n|Ship complement=150 officers and enlisted\n|Ship armament=*4 \u00d7 [[10\"/30 caliber gun|{{convert|10|in|mm|abbr=on|0}}/caliber]] breechloader rifles\n* 2 \u00d7 {{convert|4|in|mm|abbr=on}} rifles\n* 2 \u00d7 [[QF 3-pounder Hotchkiss|3-pounder]] guns\n|Ship armor=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n'''USS ''Terror''''' (Monitor No. 4)\u2014the totally rebuilt version of the earlier [[Monitor (warship)|monitor]] {{USS|Agamenticus|1863|2}}, which had shared the ''Terror's'' name\u2014was an iron-hulled, twin-screw, double-turreted [[Monitor (warship)|monitor]] of the {{sclass-|Amphitrite|monitor|4}}; on June 23, 1874 by order of President [[Ulysses S. Grant]]'s Secretary of Navy [[George M. Robeson]] in response to the [[Virginius Incident]] laid down (''scrapped and rebuilt'') at [[Philadelphia]] contracted by [[William Cramp & Sons]]. Her construction progressed over the next three years until suspended in 1877. Work was resumed six years later, and the monitor was launched on 24 March 1883.\n\nDelivered to the [[United States Navy|Navy]] in 1887, the still-unfinished warship was taken to the [[New York Navy Yard]] for completion. Over the next seven years, she fitted out at a leisurely pace. ''Terror'' was finally commissioned at [[New York City]] on 15 April 1896, with [[Captain (United States O-6)|Captain]] Purnell Frederick Harrington in command.\n\n==Service history==\n\n===Spanish\u2013American War===\nAssigned to the [[North Atlantic Squadron]], ''Terror'' operated off the east coast of the [[United States]], from [[Tompkinsville, New York]], to [[Hampton Roads]] and [[Fort Monroe|Fort Monroe, Virginia]]; and from [[Sandy Hook, New Jersey]] to [[Charleston, South Carolina]], through the winter of 1897 and 1898. On 5 May, 1897 she collided with steam [[Yacht]] \"Penelope\"  ({{flag|United States|1891}})  off [[Hoffman Island]], [[New York]] doing $500 in damage to the Yacht.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=osu.32435066693086&view=1up&seq=32 |page={{#expr:32-6}} |title=Annual report of the Supervising Inspector-general Steamboat-inspection Service, Year ending June 30, 1898 ||location=Washington |publisher=Government Printing Office |date=1897|via=Haithi Trust |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.loc.gov/resource/sn83030180/1897-05-06/ed-1/?sp=7&st=text&r=0.165,0.251,0.521,0.515,0 |title=Image 7 of New York journal and advertiser (New York [N.Y.]), May 6, 1897 |publisher=Library of Congress |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> The mysterious explosion which wrecked the [[armored cruiser]] {{USS|Maine|ACR-1|2}} at [[Havana]] Harbor on 15 February 1898 materially increased tensions between the United States and [[Spain]]. ''Terror'' sped south from Tompkinsville to join the fleet concentrating in southern waters and arrived at [[Key West]] on 2 April 1898.\n\nOn 22 April, after receiving orders from [[President of the United States|President]] [[William McKinley]], [[Rear admiral (United States)|Rear Admiral]] [[William T. Sampson]], commanding the North Atlantic Squadron from {{USS|New York|ACR-2|2}} (Armored Cruiser No. 2), deployed his fleet in preparation for a blockade of the [[Cuba]]n coast. Three days later, the United States [[Declaration of war|declared war]] on Spain, beginning the [[Spanish\u2013American War]]. ''Terror'', which had arrived off [[Cardenas de Cuba|Cardenas, Cuba]], on the 24th, captured a Cuban vessel\u2014''Almansas''\u2014on the first day of hostilities, but later released her. Over the next two days, the monitor took two Spanish ships, ''Ambrosia Bolivar'' and ''Guido'', and sent the prizes to [[Florida]].\n\nMeanwhile, the whereabouts of the Spanish Navy's ''Caribbean Squadron'' under [[Admiral]] [[Pascual Cervera y Topete|Pascual Cervera]] prompted concern in naval circles in [[Washington, D.C.|Washington]]. Intelligence estimates which reached Sampson noted that the Spanish fleet had departed the [[Cape Verde|Cape Verde Islands]] on the morning of 29 April. Sampson reacted by deciding to meet Cervera's fleet at [[San Juan, Puerto Rico]], the nearest Spanish base in the [[Caribbean|West Indies]]. With his flag in ''New York'', Rear Admiral Sampson scraped together a makeshift squadron\u2014which included ''Terror'' and a sistership, {{USS|Amphitrite|1883|2}} (Monitor No. 2), as well as battleships {{USS|Iowa|BB-4|2}} (Battleship No. 4) and {{USS|Indiana|BB-1|2}}  (Battleship No. 1), {{USS|Porter|TB-6|2}} (Torpedo Boat No. 6), two auxiliaries and a collier\u2014and departed Key West on 3 May.\n\n''Terror'' and ''Amphitrite'' broke down frequently en route and materially delayed Sampson's passage. At one point, ''New York'' took both ''Terror'' and ''Porter'' in tow. Upon arrival off San Juan on 12 May, the Americans found only a couple of minor Spanish gunboats in the harbor. In order to \"develop their positions and strength\", Sampson decided to conduct a brief bombardment of the shore defenses. The squadron stood in for their target at 04:00, on 12 May 1898, with the ships cleared for action and the lights of the town clearly visible in the predawn darkness. Sounding general quarters at 05:00, the Americans opened fire within 15 minutes, and the Spanish began returning fire at 05:23.\n\n''Terror'' stood in, fifth in column, duelling with the Spanish shore batteries in a spirited engagement for the next three hours. As the action wore on, a tremendous volume of white smoke restricted visibility and caused the Admiral to signal \"use large guns only\" to cut down on the volume of smoke.\n\n''Terror'' expended thirty-one 10-inch shells in three firing passes