{"title_page": "The Dorchester Review", "text_new": "{{Infobox magazine\n| title              = The Dorchester Review\n| image_file         = File:The_Dorchester_Review_logo.png\n| image_caption      = \n| editor             = C.P. Champion, Michael R. Jackson Bonner, James W.J. Bowden, [[F.H. Buckley]], David Twiston Davies, Philip Marchand, John Pepall, Phyllis Reeve, [[Alastair Sweeny]]<ref>Masthead of Vol. 9, No. 1, Spring/Summer 2019 (print edition).</ref><ref>https://www.dorchesterreview.ca/pages/about-the-author</ref>\n| editor_title       = Editors\n| frequency          = Semi-annual\n| circulation        = 800\n| category           = History and culture\n| publisher          = \n| founder            = C.P. Champion\n| firstdate          = {{start date and age|2011|06|1}}\n| country            = [[Canada]]\n| based              = [[Ottawa]]\n| language           = [[English language|English]]\n| website            = {{URL|www.dorchesterreview.ca}}\n| issn               = 1925-7600\n}}\n\n'''''The Dorchester Review''''' is a semi-annual, semi-academic journal of history and historical commentary founded in 2011 and published in [[Ottawa]], [[Canada]]. The magazine describes itself as a non-partisan but \"robustly polemical\" outlet for \"elements of tradition and culture inherent to Canadian experience that fail to conform to a stridently progressivist narrative.\" \n\n==Contents==\nThe journal is named after Sir [[Guy Carleton, 1st Baron Dorchester]], Governor of the [[Province of Quebec (1763\u20131791)|Province of Quebec]] and [[British North America]]. The choice of \"a bewigged British soldier, an ... unapologetic colonial governor from the pre-democratic era\" is intended to underscore the magazine's belief that \"history consists of more than a parade of [[secularism|secular]] [[modernity|modern]] progressives.\"<ref>The Dorchester Review, Vol. 1, No. 1, Spring/Summer 2011, pp. 2-3.</ref> Its core readership consists of 50% professionals and businesspeople, 10% academics, 15-20% politicians, and 20-25% eclectic readers.<ref name=Kay>{{Cite web|url=https://nationalpost.com/opinion/barbara-kay-the-dorchester-review-the-little-magazine-that-can|title=The Dorchester Review \u2014 the little magazine that can|work=[[National Post]]|date=24 May 2016|accessdate=3 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Editorial stance===\n\n''[[National Post]]'' columnist [[Barbara Kay]] described the ''Dorchester Review'' as \"politically incorrect and iconoclastic\" writing which resists \"the prevailing progressivist view that historians must choose between a right and wrong side of history,\" without catering to a specific ideology. [[Jonathan Kay]] has described it as \"the only high-level publication in Canada that examines our history and traditions without even a passing nod to academic fashions and [[identity politics]].\"<ref name=Kay/> Academic Jerry White has cited ''The Dorchester Review'' among works that \"might...prompt readers to rethink the way in which not all liberals are Liberals and not all conservatives sound like the Conservatives.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://reviewcanada.ca/magazine/2013/06/political-inheritance/|title=Political Inheritance|author=Jerry White|work=[[Literary Review of Canada]]|date=June 2013 |accessdate=17 December 2017}}</ref> Former Conservative Prime Minister [[Stephen Harper]] was observed reading the magazine in Canada's [[House of Commons]], contributing to its image as a [[right-wing politics|right-wing]] publication.<ref name=Kay/> Founding editor C.P. Champion was a senior policy advisor to [[Conservative]] cabinet minister [[Jason Kenney]]. He is a Visiting Research Fellow at the Centre for International Defence Policy at Queen's University, and the author of ''The Strange Demise of British Canada: The Liberals and Canadian Nationalism, 1964-1968'' (McGill-Queen's University Press, 2010) and ''Relentless Struggle: Saving the Army Reserve 1995-2019'', published by Durnovaria Press,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://torontosun.com/opinion/columnists/taylor-the-battle-to-save-the-canadian-forces-army-reserve|title=The battle to save the Canadian Forces' army reserve|author=Gil Taylor|work=[[Toronto Sun]]|date=19 September 2019|accessdate=23 September 2019}}</ref> which Champion founded in 2019.{{citation needed|date=December 2019}} The link between the periodical and the publishing label is suggested by the name, [[Durnovaria]], which was \"the [Latin] name of the Roman town of Dorchester.\"\n\n==See also==\n{{columns-list|colwidth=20em|\n* [[Conservatism in Canada]]\n* [[Canadian nationalism]]\n* [[List of Canadian magazines]]\n* [[List of literary magazines]]\n* [[Tory]]\n* [[Traditionalist conservatism]]\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://www.dorchesterreview.ca/}}\n\n==Notable contributors==\t\t\n{{div col|colwidth=18em}}\t\n \n* [[George Jonas]]\t\n* [[Kevin Myers]] (Ireland)\t\n* [[Gregory Melleuish]] (Australia)\t\t\n* [[Barbara Kay]]\t\t\n* [[Andrew Roberts (historian)|Andrew Roberts]] (historian)\t\t\n* [[Conrad Black]]\t\t\n* [[John Howard]] (Australia)\t\t\n* [[Alastair Sweeny]]\t\t\n* [[Roger Noriega]]\t\t\n* [[Gil Troy]]\n* [[Peter John Elliott]] (bishop)\t\n* [[Paul Hollander]]\n* [[Mathieu Bock-C\u00f4t\u00e9]]\t\n* [[Richard Lebrun]]\t\n* [[Gary Mauser]]\t\t\n* [[David Frum]]\t\t\n* [[Serge Joyal]]\t\t\n* [[John O'Sullivan (columnist)|John O\u2019Sullivan]] (columnist)\t\t\n* [[Hugh Bicheno]]\t\t\n* [[Julian Thompson (soldier)|Julian Thompson]]\t\t\n* [[Barry Gough]]\n* [[J.L. Granatstein]]\t\t\n* [[Jonathan Kay]]\t\t\n* [[Andrew P.W. Bennett]]\t\t\n* [[Noah Richler]]\t\t\n* [[Lionel Albert]]\t\t\n* [[Paul Cowan (journalist)|Paul Cowan]]\t\n* [[Pat Stogran]]\t\n* [[Ian Brodie]]\t\t\n* [[Randall Hansen]]\t\t\t\n* [[F.H. Buckley]]\t\t\n* [[Kevin Gutzman]]\t\t\n* [[Jonathon Riley (British Army officer)|Jonathon Riley]]\t\t\n* [[Rory MacLean]]\t\t\n* [[Andrew Godefroy]]\t\t\n* [[J\u00fcrgen R\u00fcttgers]] (Germany)\t\t\t\t\n* [[Randy Boyagoda]]\t\t\n* [[Tom Flanagan (political scientist)|Tom Flanagan]]\t\t\n* [[Frank Dik\u00f6tter]] (Hong Kong)\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dorchester Review, The}}\n[[Category:Magazines established in 2011]]\n[[Category:Canadian cultural magazines]]\n[[Category:Cultural magazines]]\n[[Category:Canadian history magazines]]\n[[Category:Paleoconservatism]]\n[[Category:2011 establishments in Canada]]\n[[Category:Magazines published in Ottawa]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox magazine\n| title              = The Dorchester Review\n| image_file         = File:The_Dorchester_Review_logo.png\n| image_caption      = \n| editor             = C.P. Champion, Michael R. Jackson Bonner, James W.J. Bowden, [[F.H. Buckley]], David Twiston Davies, Philip Marchand, John Pepall, Phyllis Reeve, [[Alastair Sweeny]]<ref>Masthead of Vol. 9, No. 1, Spring/Summer 2019 (print edition).</ref><ref>https://www.dorchesterreview.ca/pages/about-the-author</ref>\n| editor_title       = Editors\n| frequency          = Semi-annual\n| circulation        = 800\n| category           = History and culture\n| publisher          = \n| founder            = C.P. Champion\n| firstdate          = {{start date and age|2011|06|1}}\n| country            = [[Canada]]\n| based              = [[Ottawa]]\n| language           = [[English language|English]]\n| website            = {{URL|www.dorchesterreview.ca}}\n| issn               = 1925-7600\n}}\n\n'''''The Dorchester Review''''' is a semi-annual, semi-academic journal of history and historical commentary founded in 2011 and published in [[Ottawa]], [[Canada]]. The magazine describes itself as a non-partisan but \"robustly polemical\" outlet for \"elements of tradition and culture inherent to Canadian experience that fail to conform to a stridently progressivist narrative.\" \n\n==Contents==\nThe journal is named after Sir [[Guy Carleton, 1st Baron Dorchester]], Governor of the [[Province of Quebec (1763\u20131791)|Province of Quebec]] and [[British North America]]. The choice of \"a bewigged British soldier, an ... unapologetic colonial governor from the pre-democratic era\" is intended to underscore the magazine's belief that \"history consists of more than a parade of [[secularism|secular]] [[modernity|modern]] progressives.\"<ref>The Dorchester Review, Vol. 1, No. 1, Spring/Summer 2011, pp. 2-3.</ref> Its core readership consists of 50% professionals and businesspeople, 10% academics, 15-20% politicians, and 20-25% eclectic readers.<ref name=Kay>{{Cite web|url=https://nationalpost.com/opinion/barbara-kay-the-dorchester-review-the-little-magazine-that-can|title=The Dorchester Review \u2014 the little magazine that can|work=[[National Post]]|date=24 May 2016|accessdate=3 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Editorial stance===\n\n''[[National Post]]'' columnist [[Barbara Kay]] described the ''Dorchester Review'' as \"politically incorrect and iconoclastic\" writing which resists \"the prevailing progressivist view that historians must choose between a right and wrong side of history,\" without catering to a specific ideology. [[Jonathan Kay]] has described it as \"the only high-level publication in Canada that examines our history and traditions without even a passing nod to academic fashions and [[identity politics]].\"<ref name=Kay/> Academic Jerry White has cited ''The Dorchester Review'' among works that \"might...prompt readers to rethink the way in which not all liberals are Liberals and not all conservatives sound like the Conservatives.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://reviewcanada.ca/magazine/2013/06/political-inheritance/|title=Political Inheritance|author=Jerry White|work=[[Literary Review of Canada]]|date=June 2013 |accessdate=17 December 2017}}</ref> Former Conservative Prime Minister [[Stephen Harper]] was observed reading the magazine in Canada's [[House of Commons]], contributing to its image as a [[right-wing politics|right-wing]] publication.<ref name=Kay/> Founding editor C.P. Champion was a senior policy advisor to [[Conservative]] cabinet minister [[Jason Kenney]]. He is a Visiting Research Fellow at the Centre for International Defence Policy at Queen's University, and the author of ''The Strange Demise of British Canada: The Liberals and Canadian Nationalism, 1964-1968'' (McGill-Queen's University Press, 2010) and ''Relentless Struggle: Saving the Army Reserve 1995-2019'' published by Durnovaria Press,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://torontosun.com/opinion/columnists/taylor-the-battle-to-save-the-canadian-forces-army-reserve|title=The battle to save the Canadian Forces' army reserve|author=Gil Taylor|work=[[Toronto Sun]]|date=19 September 2019|accessdate=23 September 2019}}</ref> which Champion founded in 2019.{{citation needed|date=December 2019}} The link between the periodical and the publishing label is suggested by the name, [[Durnovaria]], which was \"the [Latin] name of the Roman town of Dorchester.\"\n\n==See also==\n{{columns-list|colwidth=20em|\n* [[Conservatism in Canada]]\n* [[Canadian nationalism]]\n* [[List of Canadian magazines]]\n* [[List of literary magazines]]\n* [[Tory]]\n* [[Traditionalist conservatism]]\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://www.dorchesterreview.ca/}}\n\n==Notable contributors==\t\t\n{{div col|colwidth=18em}}\t\n \n* [[George Jonas]]\t\n* [[Kevin Myers]] (Ireland)\t\n* [[Gregory Melleuish]] (Australia)\t\t\n* [[Barbara Kay]]\t\t\n* [[Andrew Roberts (historian)|Andrew Roberts]] (historian)\t\t\n* [[Conrad Black]]\t\t\n* [[John Howard]] (Australia)\t\t\n* [[Alastair Sweeny]]\t\t\n* [[Roger Noriega]]\t\t\n* [[Gil Troy]]\n* [[Peter John Elliott]] (bishop)\t\n* [[Paul Hollander]]\n* [[Mathieu Bock-C\u00f4t\u00e9]]\t\n* [[Richard Lebrun]]\t\n* [[Gary Mauser]]\t\t\n* [[David Frum]]\t\t\n* [[Serge Joyal]]\t\t\n* [[John O'Sullivan (columnist)|John O\u2019Sullivan]] (columnist)\t\t\n* [[Hugh Bicheno]]\t\t\n* [[Julian Thompson (soldier)|Julian Thompson]]\t\t\n* [[Barry Gough]]\n* [[J.L. Granatstein]]\t\t\n* [[Jonathan Kay]]\t\t\n* [[Andrew P.W. Bennett]]\t\t\n* [[Noah Richler]]\t\t\n* [[Lionel Albert]]\t\t\n* [[Paul Cowan (journalist)|Paul Cowan]]\t\n* [[Pat Stogran]]\t\n* [[Ian Brodie]]\t\t\n* [[Randall Hansen]]\t\t\t\n* [[F.H. Buckley]]\t\t\n* [[Kevin Gutzman]]\t\t\n* [[Jonathon Riley (British Army officer)|Jonathon Riley]]\t\t\n* [[Rory MacLean]]\t\t\n* [[Andrew Godefroy]]\t\t\n* [[J\u00fcrgen R\u00fcttgers]] (Germany)\t\t\t\t\n* [[Randy Boyagoda]]\t\t\n* [[Tom Flanagan (political scientist)|Tom Flanagan]]\t\t\n* [[Frank Dik\u00f6tter]] (Hong Kong)\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dorchester Review, The}}\n[[Category:Magazines established in 2011]]\n[[Category:Canadian cultural magazines]]\n[[Category:Cultural magazines]]\n[[Category:Canadian history magazines]]\n[[Category:Paleoconservatism]]\n[[Category:2011 establishments in Canada]]\n[[Category:Magazines published in Ottawa]]\n", "name_user": "Escandar", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEditorial stance", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Dorchester_Review"}
